# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: enthalpy-of-vaporization
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Acetone is miscible with water and serves as an important organic solvent in industry, home, and laboratory.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] About 6.7 million tonnes were produced worldwide in 2010, mainly for use as a solvent and for production of methyl methacrylate and bisphenol A, which are precursors to widely used plastics.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] It is a common building block in organic chemistry.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] It serves as a solvent in household products such as nail polish remover and paint thinner.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] It has volatile organic compound (VOC)-exempt status in the United States.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Acetone is produced and disposed of in the human body through normal metabolic processes.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Small quantities of it are present naturally in blood and urine.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] People with diabetic ketoacidosis produce it in larger amounts.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Medical ketogenic diets that increase ketone bodies (acetone, β-hydroxybutyric acid and acetoacetic acid) in the blood are used to suppress epileptic attacks in children with treatment-resistant epilepsy.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] From the 17th century, and before modern developments in organic chemistry nomenclature, acetone was given many different names.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] They included "spirit of Saturn", which was given when it was thought to be a compound of lead and, later, "pyro-acetic spirit" and "pyro-acetic ester".
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Prior to the name "acetone" being coined by French chemists, it was named "mesit" (from the Greek μεσίτης, meaning mediator) by Carl Reichenbach, who also said that methyl alcohol consisted of mesit and ethyl alcohol.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Names derived from mesit include mesitylene and mesityl oxide which were first synthesised from acetone.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] In 1839, the name "acetone" began to be used, because it was obtained from acetic acid.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Unlike many compounds with the *acet-* prefix which have a 2-carbon chain, acetone has a 3-carbon chain.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] That has caused confusion because there can not be a ketone with 2 carbons.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] The prefix refers to acetone's relation to vinegar (*acetum* in Latin, also the source of the words "acid" and "acetic"), rather than its chemical structure.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Acetone was first produced by Andreas Libavius in 1606 by distillation of lead(II) acetate.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] In 1832, French chemist Jean-Baptiste Dumas and German chemist Justus von Liebig determined the empirical formula for acetone.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] In 1833, French chemists Antoine Bussy and Michel Chevreul decided to name acetone by adding the suffix *-one* to the stem of the corresponding acid (viz, acetic acid) just as a similarly prepared product of what was then confused with margaric acid was named margarone.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] By 1852, Alexander William Williamson, an English chemist, realized that acetone was methyl acetyl; the following year, the French chemist Charles Frédéric Gerhardt concurred.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] In 1865, a German chemist, August Kekulé published the modern structural formula for acetone.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Johann Josef Loschmidt had presented the structure of acetone in 1861, but his privately published booklet received little attention.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] During World War I, Chaim Weizmann developed the biochemical process for industrial production of acetone (Weizmann Process).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Acetone is produced directly or indirectly from propene.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Approximately 83% of acetone is produced via the cumene process; as a result, acetone production is tied to phenol production.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Other processes involve the direct oxidation of propylene (Wacker-Hoechst process), or the hydration of propylene to give 2-propanol, which is oxidized (dehydrogenated) to acetone.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Previously, acetone was produced by the dry distillation of acetates, for example calcium acetate in ketonic decarboxylation.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] After that time during World War I, acetone was produced using acetone-butanol-ethanol fermentation with *Clostridium acetobutylicum* bacteria, which was developed by Chaim Weizmann (later the first president of Israel) in order to help the British war effort, in the preparation of Cordite.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] This acetone-butanol-ethanol fermentation was eventually abandoned when newer methods with better yields were found.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] In 2010, the worldwide production capacity for acetone was estimated at 6.7 million tonnes per year.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] With 1.56 million tonnes per year, the United States had the highest production capacity, followed by Taiwan and China.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] The largest producer of acetone is INEOS Phenol, owning 17% of the world's capacity, with also significant capacity (7–8%) by Mitsui, Sunoco and Shell in 2010.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] INEOS Phenol also owns the world's largest production site (420,000 tonnes/annum) in Beveren, Belgium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] The spot price of acetone in summer 2011 was 1100–1250 USD/tonne in the United States.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Humans exhale several milligrams of acetone per day and it arises from the decarboxylation of acetoacetate.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Small amounts of acetone are produced in the body by the decarboxylation of ketone bodies.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Certain dietary patterns including prolonged fasting and high-fat low-carbohydrate dieting, can produce ketosis, in which acetone is formed in body tissue.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Certain health conditions, such as alcoholism and diabetes, can produce ketoacidosis, uncontrollable ketosis that leads to a sharp, and potentially fatal, increase in the acidity of the blood.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Since it is a byproduct of fermentation, acetone is a byproduct of the distillery industry.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] It is produced by terrestrial vegetation, undefined ocean processes, incomplete combustion of biomass, or oxidation of hydrocarbons in the atmosphere.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Like most ketones, acetone exhibits the keto–enol tautomerism in which the nominal keto structure (CH3)2C=O of acetone itself is in equilibrium with the enol isomer (CH3)C(OH)=(CH2) (**prop-1-en-2-ol**).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] In acetone vapor at ambient temperature, only 2.4×10−7% of the molecules are in the enol form.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] In the presence of suitable catalysts, two acetone molecules also combine to form the compound diacetone alcohol (CH3)C=O(CH2)C(OH)(CH3)2, which on dehydration gives mesityl oxide (CH3)C=O(CH)=C(CH3)2.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] This product can further combine with another acetone molecule, with loss of another molecule of water, yielding phorone and other compounds.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Acetone is a weak Lewis base that forms adducts with soft acids like I2 and hard acids like phenol.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Acetone also forms complexes with divalent metals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Under ultraviolet light, acetone fluoresces.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] The flame temperature of pure acetone is 1980 °C.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] At its melting point (−96 °C) is claimed to polymerize to give a white elastic solid, soluble in acetone, stable for several hours at room temperature.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] To do so, a vapor of acetone is co-condensed with magnesium as a catalyst onto a very cold surface.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] The outcome of irradiation of acetone is wavelength dependent.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] The latter process is relevant to the atmospheric chemistry of acetone.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Acetone can then be metabolized either by CYP2E1 via methylglyoxal to D-lactate and pyruvate, and ultimately glucose/energy, or by a different pathway via propylene glycol to pyruvate, lactate, acetate (usable for energy) and propionaldehyde.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] About a third of the world's acetone is used as a solvent, and a quarter is consumed as acetone cyanohydrin, a precursor to methyl methacrylate.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Acetone is used to synthesize methyl methacrylate.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] The third major use of acetone (about 20%) is synthesizing bisphenol A.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Bisphenol A is a component of many polymers such as polycarbonates, polyurethanes, and epoxy resins.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Many millions of kilograms of acetone are consumed in the production of the solvents methyl isobutyl alcohol and methyl isobutyl ketone.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] These products arise via an initial aldol condensation to give diacetone alcohol.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Condensation with acetylene gives 2-methylbut-3-yn-2-ol, precursor to synthetic terpenes and terpenoids.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Acetone is a good solvent for many plastics and some synthetic fibers.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] It is used for thinning polyester resin, cleaning tools used with it, and dissolving two-part epoxies and superglue before they harden.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] It is used as one of the volatile components of some paints and varnishes.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Although itself flammable, acetone is used extensively as a solvent for the safe transportation and storage of acetylene, which cannot be safely pressurized as a pure compound.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Vessels containing a porous material are first filled with acetone followed by acetylene, which dissolves into the acetone.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] One litre of acetone can dissolve around 250 litres of acetylene at a pressure of 10 bars (1.0 MPa).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Acetone is used as a solvent by the pharmaceutical industry and as a denaturant in denatured alcohol.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Acetone is also present as an excipient in some pharmaceutical drugs.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] A variety of organic reactions employ acetone as a polar, aprotic solvent, e.g. the Jones oxidation.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Because acetone is cheap, volatile, and dissolves or decomposes with most laboratory chemicals, an acetone rinse is the standard technique to remove solid residues from laboratory glassware before a final wash.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Despite common desiccatory use, acetone dries only via bulk displacement and dilution.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] It forms no azeotropes with water (see azeotrope tables).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Acetone also removes certain stains from microscope slides.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] An acetone/dry ice mixture cools many low-temperature reactions.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Make-up artists use acetone to remove skin adhesive from the netting of wigs and mustaches by immersing the item in an acetone bath, then removing the softened glue residue with a stiff brush.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Acetone is a main ingredient in many nail polish removers because it breaks down nail polish.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] It is used for all types of nail polish removal, like gel nail polish, dip powder and acrylic nails.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] The chemical modifies peptides, both at α- or ε-amino groups, and in a poorly understood but rapid modification of certain glycine residues.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] In pathology, acetone helps find lymph nodes in fatty tissues (such as the mesentery) for tumor staging.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] The liquid dissolves the fat and hardens the nodes, making them easier to find.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Dermatologists use acetone with alcohol for acne treatments to chemically peel dry skin.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Common agents used for chemical peeling are salicylic acid, glycolic acid, azelaic acid, 30% salicylic acid in ethanol, and trichloroacetic acid (TCA).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Prior to chemexfoliation, the skin is cleaned and excess fat removed in a process called defatting, using acetone, hexachlorophene, or a combination of these agents.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Acetone has been shown to have anticonvulsant effects in animal models of epilepsy, in the absence of toxicity, when administered in millimolar concentrations.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] It has been hypothesized that the high-fat low-carbohydrate ketogenic diet used clinically to control drug-resistant epilepsy in children works by elevating acetone in the brain.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Because of their higher energy requirements, children have higher acetone production than most adults – and the younger the child, the higher the expected production.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] This indicates that children are not uniquely susceptible to acetone exposure.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] External exposures are small compared to the exposures associated with the ketogenic diet.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Acetone has a relatively long lifetime in the atmosphere of about 2 weeks.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Because of its long lifetime, it can be transported by atmospheric winds to the upper troposphere and lower stratosphere where it can influence hydrogen radical (HOx) production and ozone (O3) levels.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] These two peroxy radicals can then undergo a series of reactions to produce hydrogen oxide radicals (HOx) and can therefore have a significant impact on atmospheric chemistry including concentration of ozone (O3) in the upper troposphere.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Photolysis is just one possible processes that removes acetone from the atmosphere.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Acetone can also be removed by ocean processes and by deposition to dry land surfaces.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] The contributions of each sink to the removal of acetone from the atmosphere is still not fully understood.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Acetone's most hazardous property is its extreme flammability.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] In small amounts, acetone burns with a dull blue flame; in larger amounts, fuel evaporation causes incomplete combustion and a bright yellow flame.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] When above acetone's flash point of −20 °C (−4 °F), air mixtures of 2.5‑12.8% acetone (by volume) may explode or cause a flash fire.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Vapors can flow along surfaces to distant ignition sources and flash back.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Static discharge may ignite acetone vapors, though acetone has a very high ignition initiation energy and accidental ignition is rare.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Acetone's auto-ignition temperature is relatively high 465 °C (869 °F); moreover, auto-ignition temperature depends upon experimental conditions, such as exposure time, and has been quoted as high as 535 °C.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Even pouring or spraying acetone over red-glowing coal will not ignite it, due to the high vapour concentration and the cooling effect of evaporation.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Acetone should be stored away from strong oxidizers, such as concentrated nitric and sulfuric acid mixtures.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] It may explode when stored with chloroform in the presence of a base.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] When oxidized without combustion, for example with hydrogen peroxide, acetone may form acetone peroxide, a highly unstable primary explosive.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Acetone peroxide may be formed accidentally, e.g. when waste peroxide is poured into waste solvents.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Acetone occurs naturally as part of certain metabolic processes in the human body, and has been studied extensively and is believed to exhibit only slight toxicity in normal use.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] There is no strong evidence of chronic health effects if basic precautions are followed.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] It is generally recognized to have low acute and chronic toxicity if ingested and/or inhaled.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Acetone is not regarded as a carcinogen, a mutagen, or a concern for chronic neurotoxicity effects.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Acetone can be found as an ingredient in a variety of consumer products ranging from cosmetics to processed and unprocessed foods.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] The United States Food and Drug Administration rates acetone as a generally recognized as safe (GRAS) substance when present in food and drink at concentrations from 5 to 8 mg/L.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Acetone is an irritant, causing mild skin and moderate-to-severe eye irritation.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Like many other solvents, acetone may depress the central nervous system at high vapor concentrations.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] Acute toxicity for mice by ingestion (LD50) is 3 g/kg, and by inhalation (LC50) is 44 g/m3 over 4 hours.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] In 1995, the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) removed acetone from the list of volatile organic compounds.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] In making its decision EPA conducted an extensive review of the available toxicity data on acetone, which was continued through the 2000s.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/acetone] It found that the evaluable "data are inadequate for an assessment of the human carcinogenic potential of acetone".
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] A soft, silvery-white radioactive metal, actinium reacts rapidly with oxygen and moisture in air, forming a white coating of actinium oxide that prevents further oxidation.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] As with most lanthanides and many actinides, actinium assumes oxidation state +3 in nearly all its chemical compounds.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Actinium is found only in traces in uranium and thorium ores as the isotope 227Ac, which decays with a half-life of 21.772 years, predominantly emitting beta and sometimes alpha particles, and 228Ac, which is beta active with a half-life of 6.15 hours.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] One tonne of natural uranium in ore contains about 0.2 milligrams of actinium-227, and one tonne of thorium contains about 5 nanograms of actinium-228.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] The close similarity of physical and chemical properties of actinium and lanthanum makes the separation of actinium from the ore impractical.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Instead, the element is prepared, in milligram amounts, by the neutron irradiation of 226Ra in a nuclear reactor.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Owing to its scarcity, high price, and radioactivity, actinium has no significant industrial use.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Its current applications include a neutron source and an agent for radiation therapy.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] André-Louis Debierne, a French chemist, announced the discovery of a new element in 1899.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] He separated it from pitchblende residues left by Marie and Pierre Curie after they had extracted radium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] In 1899, Debierne described the substance as similar to titanium and (in 1900) as similar to thorium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Friedrich Oskar Giesel found in 1902 a substance similar to lanthanum and called it "emanium" in 1904.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Articles published in the 1970s and later suggest that Debierne's results published in 1904 conflict with those reported in 1899 and 1900.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] This has led some authors to advocate that Giesel alone should be credited with the discovery.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] A less confrontational vision of scientific discovery is proposed by Adloff.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] He suggests that hindsight criticism of the early publications should be mitigated by the then nascent state of radiochemistry: highlighting the prudence of Debierne's claims in the original papers, he notes that nobody can contend that Debierne's substance did not contain actinium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Debierne, who is now considered by the vast majority of historians as the discoverer, lost interest in the element and left the topic.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Giesel, on the other hand, can rightfully be credited with the first preparation of radiochemically pure actinium and with the identification of its atomic number 89.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] The name actinium originates from the Ancient Greek *aktis, aktinos* (ακτίς, ακτίνος), meaning beam or ray.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Its symbol Ac is also used in abbreviations of other compounds that have nothing to do with actinium, such as acetyl, acetate and sometimes acetaldehyde.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Actinium is a soft, silvery-white, radioactive, metallic element.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Its estimated shear modulus is similar to that of lead.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Owing to its strong radioactivity, actinium glows in the dark with a pale blue light, which originates from the surrounding air ionized by the emitted energetic particles.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Actinium has similar chemical properties to lanthanum and other lanthanides, and therefore these elements are difficult to separate when extracting from uranium ores.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Solvent extraction and ion chromatography are commonly used for the separation.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] The first element of the actinides, actinium, gave the set its name, much as lanthanum had done for the lanthanides.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] The actinides are much more diverse than the lanthanides and therefore it was not until 1945 that the most significant change to Dmitri Mendeleev's periodic table since the recognition of the lanthanides, the introduction of the actinides, was generally accepted after Glenn T.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Seaborg's research on the transuranium elements (although it had been proposed as early as 1892 by British chemist Henry Bassett).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Actinium reacts rapidly with oxygen and moisture in air, forming a white coating of actinium oxide that impedes further oxidation.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] As with most lanthanides and actinides, actinium exists in the oxidation state +3, and the Ac3+ ions are colorless in solutions.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] The oxidation state +3 originates from the [Rn] 6d17s2 electronic configuration of actinium, with three valence electrons that are easily donated to give the stable closed-shell structure of the noble gas radon.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Although the 5f orbitals are unoccupied in an actinium atom, it can be used as a valence orbital in actinium complexes and hence it is generally considered the first 5f element by authors working on it.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Ac3+ is the largest of all known tripositive ions and its first coordination sphere contains approximately 10.9 ± 0.5 water molecules.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Due to actinium's intense radioactivity, only a limited number of actinium compounds are known.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] These include: AcF3, AcCl3, AcBr3, AcOF, AcOCl, AcOBr, Ac2S3, Ac2O3, AcPO4 and Ac(NO3)3.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] They all contain actinium in the oxidation state +3.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] In particular, the lattice constants of the analogous lanthanum and actinium compounds differ by only a few percent.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Here *a*, *b* and *c* are lattice constants, No is the space group number, and *Z* is the number of formula units per unit cell.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Density was not measured directly but calculated from the lattice parameters.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Actinium oxide (Ac2O3) can be obtained by heating the hydroxide at 500 °C (932 °F) or the oxalate at 1,100 °C (2,010 °F), in vacuum.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Its crystal lattice is isotypic with the oxides of most trivalent rare-earth metals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Actinium trifluoride can be produced either in solution or in solid reaction.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] The former reaction is carried out at room temperature, by adding hydrofluoric acid to a solution containing actinium ions.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] In the latter method, actinium metal is treated with hydrogen fluoride vapors at 700 °C (1,292 °F) in an all-platinum setup.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Treating actinium trifluoride with ammonium hydroxide at 900–1,000 °C (1,650–1,830 °F) yields oxyfluoride AcOF.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Whereas lanthanum oxyfluoride can be easily obtained by burning lanthanum trifluoride in air at 800 °C (1,470 °F) for an hour, similar treatment of actinium trifluoride yields no AcOF and only results in melting of the initial product.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Actinium trichloride is obtained by reacting actinium hydroxide or oxalate with carbon tetrachloride vapors at temperatures above 960 °C (1,760 °F).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Similarly to the oxyfluoride, actinium oxychloride can be prepared by hydrolyzing actinium trichloride with ammonium hydroxide at 1,000 °C (1,830 °F).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] However, in contrast to the oxyfluoride, the oxychloride could well be synthesized by igniting a solution of actinium trichloride in hydrochloric acid with ammonia.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] and treating it with ammonium hydroxide at 500 °C (932 °F) results in the oxybromide AcOBr.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Actinium hydride was obtained by reduction of actinium trichloride with potassium at 300 °C (572 °F), and its structure was deduced by analogy with the corresponding LaH2 hydride.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] The source of hydrogen in the reaction was uncertain.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Mixing monosodium phosphate (NaH2PO4) with a solution of actinium in hydrochloric acid yields white-colored actinium phosphate hemihydrate (AcPO4·0.5H2O), and heating actinium oxalate with hydrogen sulfide vapors at 1,400 °C (2,550 °F) for a few minutes results in a black actinium sulfide Ac2S3.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] It may be produced by acting with a mixture of hydrogen sulfide and carbon disulfide on actinium oxide at 1,000 °C (1,830 °F).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Naturally occurring actinium is principally composed of two radioactive isotopes; 227Ac (from the radioactive family of 235U) and 228Ac (a granddaughter of 232Th).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] 227Ac decays mainly as a beta emitter with a very small energy, but in 1.38% of cases it emits an alpha particle, so it can readily be identified through alpha spectrometry.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Thirty-three radioisotopes have been identified, the most stable being 227Ac with a half-life of 21.772 years, 225Ac with a half-life of 10.0 days and 226Ac with a half-life of 29.37 hours.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] All remaining radioactive isotopes have half-lives that are less than 10 hours, and the majority of them have half-lives shorter than one minute.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] The shortest-lived known isotope of actinium is 217Ac (half-life of 69 nanoseconds) which decays through alpha decay.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Actinium also has two known meta states.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] The most significant isotopes for chemistry are 225Ac, 227Ac, and 228Ac.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Purified 227Ac comes into equilibrium with its decay products after about a half-year.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] It decays according to its 21.772-year half-life, emitting mostly beta (98.62%) and some alpha particles (1.38%); the successive decay products are part of the actinium series.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Owing to the low available amounts, low energy of its beta particles (maximum 44.8 keV) and low intensity of alpha radiation, 227Ac is difficult to detect directly by its emission, and it is therefore traced via its decay products.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] The isotopes of actinium range in atomic weight from 203 Da (203Ac) to 236 Da (236Ac).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Actinium is found only in traces in uranium ores – one tonne of uranium in ore contains about 0.2 milligrams of 227Ac – and in thorium ores, which contain about 5 nanograms of 228Ac per one tonne of thorium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] The actinium isotope 227Ac is a transient member of the uranium-actinium series decay chain, which begins with the parent isotope 235U (or 239Pu) and ends with the stable lead isotope 207Pb.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] The isotope 228Ac is a transient member of the thorium series decay chain, which begins with the parent isotope 232Th and ends with the stable lead isotope 208Pb.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] The low natural concentration and the close similarity of physical and chemical properties to those of lanthanum and other lanthanides, which are always abundant in actinium-bearing ores, render separation of actinium from the ore impractical.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] The most concentrated actinium sample prepared from raw material consisted of 7 micrograms of 227Ac in less than 0.1 milligrams of La2O3, and complete separation was never achieved.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Instead, actinium is prepared, in milligram amounts, by the neutron irradiation of 226Ra in a nuclear reactor.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] The reaction yield is about 2% of the radium weight.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] 227Ac can further capture neutrons resulting in small amounts of 228Ac.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] After the synthesis, actinium is separated from radium and from the products of decay and nuclear fusion, such as thorium, polonium, lead, and bismuth.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] The extraction can be performed with thenoyltrifluoroacetone-benzene solution from an aqueous solution of the radiation products, and the selectivity to a certain element is achieved by adjusting the pH (to about 6.0 for actinium).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] An alternative procedure is anion exchange with an appropriate resin in nitric acid, which can result in a separation factor of 1,000,000 for radium and actinium vs. thorium in a two-stage process.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Actinium can then be separated from radium, with a ratio of about 100, using a low cross-linking cation exchange resin and nitric acid as eluant.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] 225Ac was first produced artificially at the Institute for Transuranium Elements (ITU) in Germany using a cyclotron and at St George Hospital in Sydney using a linac in 2000.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] This rare isotope has potential applications in radiation therapy and is most efficiently produced by bombarding a radium-226 target with 20–30 MeV deuterium ions.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] This reaction also yields 226Ac which however decays with a half-life of 29 hours and thus does not contaminate 225Ac.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Actinium metal has been prepared by the reduction of actinium fluoride with lithium vapor in vacuum at a temperature between 1,100 and 1,300 °C (2,010 and 2,370 °F).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Higher temperatures resulted in evaporation of the product, and lower temperatures led to an incomplete transformation.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Lithium was chosen among other alkali metals because its fluoride is the most volatile.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Owing to its scarcity, high price and radioactivity, 227Ac currently has no significant industrial use, but 225Ac is currently being studied for use in cancer treatments such as targeted alpha therapies.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] 227Ac is highly radioactive and was therefore studied for use as an active element of radioisotope thermoelectric generators, for example, in spacecraft.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] The oxide of 227Ac pressed with beryllium is also an efficient neutron source with the activity exceeding that of the standard americium-beryllium and radium-beryllium pairs.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] In all those applications, 227Ac (a beta source) is merely a progenitor which generates alpha-emitting isotopes upon its decay.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] The 227AcBe neutron sources can be applied in a neutron probe – a standard device for measuring the quantity of water present in soil, as well as moisture/density for quality control in highway construction.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Such probes are also used in well logging applications, in neutron radiography, tomography, and other radiochemical investigations.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] 225Ac is applied in medicine to produce 213Bi in a reusable generator or can be used alone as an agent for radiation therapy, in particular targeted alpha therapy (TAT).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] This isotope has a half-life of 10 days, making it much more suitable for radiation therapy than 213Bi (half-life 46 minutes).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Additionally, 225Ac decays to nontoxic 209Bi rather than toxic lead, which is the final product in the decay chains of several other candidate isotopes, namely 227Th, 228Th, and 230U.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Not only 225Ac itself, but also its daughters, emit alpha particles which kill cancer cells in the body.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] The major difficulty with the application of 225Ac was that intravenous injection of simple actinium complexes resulted in their accumulation in the bones and liver for a period of tens of years.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] As a result, after the cancer cells were quickly killed by alpha particles from 225Ac, the radiation from the actinium and its daughters might induce new mutations.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] To solve this problem, 225Ac was bound to a chelating agent, such as citrate, ethylenediaminetetraacetic acid (EDTA) or diethylene triamine pentaacetic acid (DTPA).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] This reduced actinium accumulation in the bones, but the excretion from the body remained slow.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Much better results were obtained with such chelating agents as HEHA (1,4,7,10,13,16-hexaazacyclohexadecane-N,N′,N″,N‴,N‴′,N‴″-hexaacetic acid) or DOTA (1,4,7,10-tetraazacyclododecane-1,4,7,10-tetraacetic acid) coupled to trastuzumab, a monoclonal antibody that interferes with the HER2/neu receptor.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] The latter delivery combination was tested on mice and proved to be effective against leukemia, lymphoma, breast, ovarian, neuroblastoma and prostate cancers.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] The medium half-life of 227Ac (21.77 years) makes it a very convenient radioactive isotope in modeling the slow vertical mixing of oceanic waters.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] The associated processes cannot be studied with the required accuracy by direct measurements of current velocities (of the order 50 meters per year).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] However, evaluation of the concentration depth profiles for different isotopes allows estimating the mixing rates.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] The physics behind this method is as follows: oceanic waters contain homogeneously dispersed 235U.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Its decay product, 231Pa, gradually precipitates to the bottom, so that its concentration first increases with depth and then stays nearly constant.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] 231Pa decays to 227Ac; however, the concentration of the latter isotope does not follow the 231Pa depth profile, but instead increases toward the sea bottom.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] This occurs because of the mixing processes, which raise some additional 227Ac from the sea bottom.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Thus, analysis of both 231Pa and 227Ac depth profiles allows researchers to model the mixing behavior.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] There are theoretical predictions that AcHx hydrides (in this case with very high pressure) are a candidate for a near room-temperature superconductor as they have Tc significantly higher than H3S, possibly near 250 K.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] 227Ac is highly radioactive and experiments with it are carried out in a specially designed laboratory equipped with a tight glove box.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] When actinium trichloride is administered intravenously to rats, about 33% of actinium is deposited into the bones and 50% into the liver.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] Its toxicity is comparable to, but slightly lower than, that of americium and plutonium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/actinium] For trace quantities, fume hoods with good aeration suffice; for gram amounts, hot cells with shielding from the intense gamma radiation emitted by 227Ac are necessary.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The **alkali metals** consist of the chemical elements lithium (Li), sodium (Na), potassium (K), rubidium (Rb), caesium (Cs), and francium (Fr).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Together with hydrogen they constitute group 1, which lies in the s-block of the periodic table.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] All alkali metals have their outermost electron in an s-orbital: this shared electron configuration results in them having very similar characteristic properties.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Indeed, the alkali metals provide the best example of group trends in properties in the periodic table, with elements exhibiting well-characterised homologous behaviour.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] This family of elements is also known as the **lithium family** after its leading element.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The alkali metals are all shiny, soft, highly reactive metals at standard temperature and pressure and readily lose their outermost electron to form cations with charge +1.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] They can all be cut easily with a knife due to their softness, exposing a shiny surface that tarnishes rapidly in air due to oxidation by atmospheric moisture and oxygen (and in the case of lithium, nitrogen).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Because of their high reactivity, they must be stored under oil to prevent reaction with air, and are found naturally only in salts and never as the free elements.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Caesium, the fifth alkali metal, is the most reactive of all the metals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] All the alkali metals react with water, with the heavier alkali metals reacting more vigorously than the lighter ones.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Experiments have been conducted to attempt the synthesis of element 119, which is likely to be the next member of the group; none were successful.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Most alkali metals have many different applications.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] One of the best-known applications of the pure elements is the use of rubidium and caesium in atomic clocks, of which caesium atomic clocks form the basis of the second.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] A common application of the compounds of sodium is the sodium-vapour lamp, which emits light very efficiently.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Table salt, or sodium chloride, has been used since antiquity.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Lithium finds use as a psychiatric medication and as an anode in lithium batteries.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Sodium, potassium and possibly lithium are essential elements, having major biological roles as electrolytes, and although the other alkali metals are not essential, they also have various effects on the body, both beneficial and harmful.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Sodium compounds have been known since ancient times; salt (sodium chloride) has been an important commodity in human activities.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] While potash has been used since ancient times, it was not understood for most of its history to be a fundamentally different substance from sodium mineral salts.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Georg Ernst Stahl obtained experimental evidence which led him to suggest the fundamental difference of sodium and potassium salts in 1702, and Henri-Louis Duhamel du Monceau was able to prove this difference in 1736.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The exact chemical composition of potassium and sodium compounds, and the status as chemical element of potassium and sodium, was not known then, and thus Antoine Lavoisier did not include either alkali in his list of chemical elements in 1789.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Pure potassium was first isolated in 1807 in England by Humphry Davy, who derived it from caustic potash (KOH, potassium hydroxide) by the use of electrolysis of the molten salt with the newly invented voltaic pile.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Previous attempts at electrolysis of the aqueous salt were unsuccessful due to potassium's extreme reactivity.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Potassium was the first metal that was isolated by electrolysis.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Later that same year, Davy reported extraction of sodium from the similar substance caustic soda (NaOH, lye) by a similar technique, demonstrating the elements, and thus the salts, to be different.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Petalite (LiAlSi4O10) was discovered in 1800 by the Brazilian chemist José Bonifácio de Andrada in a mine on the island of Utö, Sweden.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] However, it was not until 1817 that Johan August Arfwedson, then working in the laboratory of the chemist Jöns Jacob Berzelius, detected the presence of a new element while analysing petalite ore.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] This new element was noted by him to form compounds similar to those of sodium and potassium, though its carbonate and hydroxide were less soluble in water and more alkaline than the other alkali metals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] He named the metal inside the material *lithium*.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Lithium, sodium, and potassium were part of the discovery of periodicity, as they are among a series of triads of elements in the same group that were noted by Johann Wolfgang Döbereiner in 1850 as having similar properties.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Rubidium and caesium were the first elements to be discovered using the spectroscope, invented in 1859 by Robert Bunsen and Gustav Kirchhoff.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The next year, they discovered caesium in the mineral water from Bad Dürkheim, Germany.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Their discovery of rubidium came the following year in Heidelberg, Germany, finding it in the mineral lepidolite.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The names of rubidium and caesium come from the most prominent lines in their emission spectra: a bright red line for rubidium (from the Latin word *rubidus*, meaning dark red or bright red), and a sky-blue line for caesium (derived from the Latin word *caesius*, meaning sky-blue).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] His version put all the alkali metals then known (lithium to caesium), as well as copper, silver, and thallium (which show the +1 oxidation state characteristic of the alkali metals), together into a group.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] His table placed hydrogen with the halogens.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] After 1869, Dmitri Mendeleev proposed his periodic table placing lithium at the top of a group with sodium, potassium, rubidium, caesium, and thallium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Two years later, Mendeleev revised his table, placing hydrogen in group 1 above lithium, and also moving thallium to the boron group.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] In this 1871 version, copper, silver, and gold were placed twice, once as part of group IB, and once as part of a "group VIII" encompassing today's groups 8 to 11.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] After the introduction of the 18-column table, the group IB elements were moved to their current position in the d-block, while alkali metals were left in *group IA*.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Later the group's name was changed to *group 1* in 1988.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The trivial name "alkali metals" comes from the fact that the hydroxides of the group 1 elements are all strong alkalis when dissolved in water.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] There were at least four erroneous and incomplete discoveries before Marguerite Perey of the Curie Institute in Paris, France discovered francium in 1939 by purifying a sample of actinium-227, which had been reported to have a decay energy of 220 keV.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] However, Perey noticed decay particles with an energy level below 80 keV.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Perey thought this decay activity might have been caused by a previously unidentified decay product, one that was separated during purification, but emerged again out of the pure actinium-227.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Various tests eliminated the possibility of the unknown element being thorium, radium, lead, bismuth, or thallium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The new product exhibited chemical properties of an alkali metal (such as coprecipitating with caesium salts), which led Perey to believe that it was element 87, caused by the alpha decay of actinium-227.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Perey then attempted to determine the proportion of beta decay to alpha decay in actinium-227.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Her first test put the alpha branching at 0.6%, a figure that she later revised to 1%.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The next element below francium (eka-francium) in the periodic table would be ununennium (Uue), element 119.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The synthesis of ununennium was first attempted in 1985 by bombarding a target of einsteinium-254 with calcium-48 ions at the superHILAC accelerator at the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory in Berkeley, California.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] No atoms were identified, leading to a limiting yield of 300 nb.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] However, given that ununennium is only the first period 8 element on the extended periodic table, it may well be discovered in the near future through other reactions, and indeed an attempt to synthesise it is currently ongoing in Japan.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Currently, none of the period 8 elements has been discovered yet, and it is also possible, due to drip instabilities, that only the lower period 8 elements, up to around element 128, are physically possible.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] No attempts at synthesis have been made for any heavier alkali metals: due to their extremely high atomic number, they would require new, more powerful methods and technology to make.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The Oddo–Harkins rule holds that elements with even atomic numbers are more common than those with odd atomic numbers, with the exception of hydrogen and beryllium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] This rule argues that elements with odd atomic numbers have one unpaired proton and are more likely to capture another, thus increasing their atomic number.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] In elements with even atomic numbers, protons are paired, with each member of the pair offsetting the spin of the other, enhancing stability.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] All the alkali metals have odd atomic numbers and they are not as common as the elements with even atomic numbers adjacent to them (the noble gases and the alkaline earth metals) in the Solar System.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The heavier alkali metals are also less abundant than the lighter ones as the alkali metals from rubidium onward can only be synthesised in supernovae and not in stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The Earth formed from the same cloud of matter that formed the Sun, but the planets acquired different compositions during the formation and evolution of the Solar System.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] In turn, the natural history of the Earth caused parts of this planet to have differing concentrations of the elements.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The mass of the Earth is approximately 5.98×1024 kg.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Due to planetary differentiation, the core region is believed to be primarily composed of iron (88.8%), with smaller amounts of nickel (5.8%), sulfur (4.5%), and less than 1% trace elements.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The alkali metals, due to their high reactivity, do not occur naturally in pure form in nature.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] They are lithophiles and therefore remain close to the Earth's surface because they combine readily with oxygen and so associate strongly with silica, forming relatively low-density minerals that do not sink down into the Earth's core.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Potassium, rubidium and caesium are also incompatible elements due to their large ionic radii.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Sodium and potassium are very abundant on Earth, both being among the ten most common elements in Earth's crust; sodium makes up approximately 2.6% of the Earth's crust measured by weight, making it the sixth most abundant element overall and the most abundant alkali metal.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Potassium makes up approximately 1.5% of the Earth's crust and is the seventh most abundant element.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Sodium is found in many different minerals, of which the most common is ordinary salt (sodium chloride), which occurs in vast quantities dissolved in seawater.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Other solid deposits include halite, amphibole, cryolite, nitratine, and zeolite.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Many of these solid deposits occur as a result of ancient seas evaporating, which still occurs now in places such as Utah's Great Salt Lake and the Dead Sea.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Despite its chemical similarity, lithium typically does not occur together with sodium or potassium due to its smaller size.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Due to its relatively low reactivity, it can be found in seawater in large amounts; it is estimated that lithium concentration in seawater is approximately 0.14 to 0.25 parts per million (ppm) or 25 micromolar.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Its diagonal relationship with magnesium often allows it to replace magnesium in ferromagnesium minerals, where its crustal concentration is about 18 ppm, comparable to that of gallium and niobium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Commercially, the most important lithium mineral is spodumene, which occurs in large deposits worldwide.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Rubidium is approximately as abundant as zinc and more abundant than copper.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] It occurs naturally in the minerals leucite, pollucite, carnallite, zinnwaldite, and lepidolite, although none of these contain only rubidium and no other alkali metals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Caesium is more abundant than some commonly known elements, such as antimony, cadmium, tin, and tungsten, but is much less abundant than rubidium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Francium-223, the only naturally occurring isotope of francium, is the product of the alpha decay of actinium-227 and can be found in trace amounts in uranium minerals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] In a given sample of uranium, there is estimated to be only one francium atom for every 1018 uranium atoms.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] It has been calculated that there are at most 30 grams of francium in the earth's crust at any time, due to its extremely short half-life of 22 minutes.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The physical and chemical properties of the alkali metals can be readily explained by their having an ns1 valence electron configuration, which results in weak metallic bonding.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Hence, all the alkali metals are soft and have low densities, melting and boiling points, as well as heats of sublimation, vaporisation, and dissociation.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] They all crystallise in the body-centered cubic crystal structure, and have distinctive flame colours because their outer s electron is very easily excited.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Indeed, these flame test colours are the most common way of identifying them since all their salts with common ions are soluble.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The ns1 configuration also results in the alkali metals having very large atomic and ionic radii, as well as very high thermal and electrical conductivity.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Their chemistry is dominated by the loss of their lone valence electron in the outermost s-orbital to form the +1 oxidation state, due to the ease of ionising this electron and the very high second ionisation energy.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Most of the chemistry has been observed only for the first five members of the group.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The chemistry of francium is not well established due to its extreme radioactivity; thus, the presentation of its properties here is limited.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] What little is known about francium shows that it is very close in behaviour to caesium, as expected.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The physical properties of francium are even sketchier because the bulk element has never been observed; hence any data that may be found in the literature are certainly speculative extrapolations.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The alkali metals are more similar to each other than the elements in any other group are to each other.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Indeed, the similarity is so great that it is quite difficult to separate potassium, rubidium, and caesium, due to their similar ionic radii; lithium and sodium are more distinct.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] For instance, when moving down the table, all known alkali metals show increasing atomic radius, decreasing electronegativity, increasing reactivity, and decreasing melting and boiling points as well as heats of fusion and vaporisation.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] In general, their densities increase when moving down the table, with the exception that potassium is less dense than sodium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] One of the very few properties of the alkali metals that does not display a very smooth trend is their reduction potentials: lithium's value is anomalous, being more negative than the others.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The stable alkali metals are all silver-coloured metals except for caesium, which has a pale golden tint: it is one of only three metals that are clearly coloured (the other two being copper and gold).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Additionally, the heavy alkaline earth metals calcium, strontium, and barium, as well as the divalent lanthanides europium and ytterbium, are pale yellow, though the colour is much less prominent than it is for caesium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Their lustre tarnishes rapidly in air due to oxidation.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] All the alkali metals are highly reactive and are never found in elemental forms in nature.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Because of this, they are usually stored in mineral oil or kerosene (paraffin oil).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] They react aggressively with the halogens to form the alkali metal halides, which are white ionic crystalline compounds that are all soluble in water except lithium fluoride (LiF).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The alkali metals also react with water to form strongly alkaline hydroxides and thus should be handled with great care.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The heavier alkali metals react more vigorously than the lighter ones; for example, when dropped into water, caesium produces a larger explosion than potassium if the same number of moles of each metal is used.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The alkali metals have the lowest first ionisation energies in their respective periods of the periodic table because of their low effective nuclear charge and the ability to attain a noble gas configuration by losing just one electron.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Not only do the alkali metals react with water, but also with proton donors like alcohols and phenols, gaseous ammonia, and alkynes, the last demonstrating the phenomenal degree of their reactivity.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Their great power as reducing agents makes them very useful in liberating other metals from their oxides or halides.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The second ionisation energy of all of the alkali metals is very high as it is in a full shell that is also closer to the nucleus; thus, they almost always lose a single electron, forming cations.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The alkalide anions have filled s-subshells, which gives them enough stability to exist.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] All the stable alkali metals except lithium are known to be able to form alkalides, and the alkalides have much theoretical interest due to their unusual stoichiometry and low ionisation potentials.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Alkalides are chemically similar to the electrides, which are salts with trapped electrons acting as anions.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] In aqueous solution, the alkali metal ions form aqua ions of the formula [M(H2O)*n*]+, where *n* is the solvation number.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Their coordination numbers and shapes agree well with those expected from their ionic radii.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] In aqueous solution the water molecules directly attached to the metal ion are said to belong to the first coordination sphere, also known as the first, or primary, solvation shell.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The bond between a water molecule and the metal ion is a dative covalent bond, with the oxygen atom donating both electrons to the bond.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Each coordinated water molecule may be attached by hydrogen bonds to other water molecules.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The latter are said to reside in the second coordination sphere.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] There are also probably six water molecules in the primary solvation sphere of the sodium ion, forming the octahedral [Na(H2O)6]+ ion.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The chemistry of lithium shows several differences from that of the rest of the group as the small Li+ cation polarises anions and gives its compounds a more covalent character.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Lithium and magnesium have a diagonal relationship due to their similar atomic radii, so that they show some similarities.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] For example, lithium forms a stable nitride, a property common among all the alkaline earth metals (magnesium's group) but unique among the alkali metals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] In addition, among their respective groups, only lithium and magnesium form organometallic compounds with significant covalent character (e.g.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Lithium fluoride is the only alkali metal halide that is poorly soluble in water, and lithium hydroxide is the only alkali metal hydroxide that is not deliquescent.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Conversely, lithium perchlorate and other lithium salts with large anions that cannot be polarised are much more stable than the analogous compounds of the other alkali metals, probably because Li+ has a high solvation energy.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] This effect also means that most simple lithium salts are commonly encountered in hydrated form, because the anhydrous forms are extremely hygroscopic: this allows salts like lithium chloride and lithium bromide to be used in dehumidifiers and air-conditioners.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Francium is also predicted to show some differences due to its high atomic weight, causing its electrons to travel at considerable fractions of the speed of light and thus making relativistic effects more prominent.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Thus, contrary to expectation, caesium is the most reactive of the alkali metals, not francium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Some of the few properties of francium that have been predicted taking relativity into account are the electron affinity (47.2 kJ/mol) and the enthalpy of dissociation of the Fr2 molecule (42.1 kJ/mol).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The CsFr molecule is polarised as Cs+Fr−, showing that the 7s subshell of francium is much more strongly affected by relativistic effects than the 6s subshell of caesium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Additionally, francium superoxide (FrO2) is expected to have significant covalent character, unlike the other alkali metal superoxides, because of bonding contributions from the 6p electrons of francium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] All the alkali metals have odd atomic numbers; hence, their isotopes must be either odd–odd (both proton and neutron number are odd) or odd–even (proton number is odd, but neutron number is even).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Odd–odd nuclei have even mass numbers, whereas odd–even nuclei have odd mass numbers.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Odd–odd primordial nuclides are rare because most odd–odd nuclei are highly unstable with respect to beta decay, because the decay products are even–even, and are therefore more strongly bound, due to nuclear pairing effects.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Due to the great rarity of odd–odd nuclei, almost all the primordial isotopes of the alkali metals are odd–even (the exceptions being the light stable isotope lithium-6 and the long-lived radioisotope potassium-40).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] An effect of the instability of an odd number of either type of nucleons is that odd-numbered elements, such as the alkali metals, tend to have fewer stable isotopes than even-numbered elements.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Of the 26 monoisotopic elements that have only a single stable isotope, all but one have an odd atomic number and all but one also have an even number of neutrons.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Beryllium is the single exception to both rules, due to its low atomic number.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Caesium was also thought to be radioactive in the early 20th century, although it has no naturally occurring radioisotopes.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] (Francium had not been discovered yet at that time.) The natural long-lived radioisotope of potassium, potassium-40, makes up about 0.012% of natural potassium, and thus natural potassium is weakly radioactive.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] This natural radioactivity became a basis for a mistaken claim of the discovery for element 87 (the next alkali metal after caesium) in 1925.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Natural rubidium is similarly slightly radioactive, with 27.83% being the long-lived radioisotope rubidium-87.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Caesium-137, with a half-life of 30.17 years, is one of the two principal medium-lived fission products, along with strontium-90, which are responsible for most of the radioactivity of spent nuclear fuel after several years of cooling, up to several hundred years after use.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] It constitutes most of the radioactivity still left from the Chernobyl accident.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Caesium-137 undergoes high-energy beta decay and eventually becomes stable barium-137.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] It is a strong emitter of gamma radiation.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Caesium-137 has a very low rate of neutron capture and cannot be feasibly disposed of in this way, but must be allowed to decay.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Caesium-137 has been used as a tracer in hydrologic studies, analogous to the use of tritium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Small amounts of caesium-134 and caesium-137 were released into the environment during nearly all nuclear weapon tests and some nuclear accidents, most notably the Goiânia accident and the Chernobyl disaster.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] As of 2005, caesium-137 is the principal source of radiation in the zone of alienation around the Chernobyl nuclear power plant.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The atomic radii of the alkali metals increase going down the group.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Because of the shielding effect, when an atom has more than one electron shell, each electron feels electric repulsion from the other electrons as well as electric attraction from the nucleus.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] In the alkali metals, the outermost electron only feels a net charge of +1, as some of the nuclear charge (which is equal to the atomic number) is cancelled by the inner electrons; the number of inner electrons of an alkali metal is always one less than the nuclear charge.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Therefore, the only factor which affects the atomic radius of the alkali metals is the number of electron shells.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Since this number increases down the group, the atomic radius must also increase down the group.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The ionic radii of the alkali metals are much smaller than their atomic radii.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] This is because the outermost electron of the alkali metals is in a different electron shell than the inner electrons, and thus when it is removed the resulting atom has one fewer electron shell and is smaller.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Additionally, the effective nuclear charge has increased, and thus the electrons are attracted more strongly towards the nucleus and the ionic radius decreases.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The first ionisation energy of an element or molecule is the energy required to move the most loosely held electron from one mole of gaseous atoms of the element or molecules to form one mole of gaseous ions with electric charge +1.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The factors affecting the first ionisation energy are the nuclear charge, the amount of shielding by the inner electrons and the distance from the most loosely held electron from the nucleus, which is always an outer electron in main group elements.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The first two factors change the effective nuclear charge the most loosely held electron feels.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Since the outermost electron of alkali metals always feels the same effective nuclear charge (+1), the only factor which affects the first ionisation energy is the distance from the outermost electron to the nucleus.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Since this distance increases down the group, the outermost electron feels less attraction from the nucleus and thus the first ionisation energy decreases.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] This trend is broken in francium due to the relativistic stabilisation and contraction of the 7s orbital, bringing francium's valence electron closer to the nucleus than would be expected from non-relativistic calculations.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] This makes francium's outermost electron feel more attraction from the nucleus, increasing its first ionisation energy slightly beyond that of caesium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The second ionisation energy of the alkali metals is much higher than the first as the second-most loosely held electron is part of a fully filled electron shell and is thus difficult to remove.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The reactivities of the alkali metals increase going down the group.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] This is the result of a combination of two factors: the first ionisation energies and atomisation energies of the alkali metals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Because the first ionisation energy of the alkali metals decreases down the group, it is easier for the outermost electron to be removed from the atom and participate in chemical reactions, thus increasing reactivity down the group.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Adding the atomisation and first ionisation energies gives a quantity closely related to (but not equal to) the activation energy of the reaction of an alkali metal with another substance.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] This quantity decreases going down the group, and so does the activation energy; thus, chemical reactions can occur faster and the reactivity increases down the group.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Electronegativity is a chemical property that describes the tendency of an atom or a functional group to attract electrons (or electron density) towards itself.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] If the bond between sodium and chlorine in sodium chloride were covalent, the pair of shared electrons would be attracted to the chlorine because the effective nuclear charge on the outer electrons is +7 in chlorine but is only +1 in sodium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The electron pair is attracted so close to the chlorine atom that they are practically transferred to the chlorine atom (an ionic bond).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] However, if the sodium atom was replaced by a lithium atom, the electrons will not be attracted as close to the chlorine atom as before because the lithium atom is smaller, making the electron pair more strongly attracted to the closer effective nuclear charge from lithium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Hence, the larger alkali metal atoms (further down the group) will be less electronegative as the bonding pair is less strongly attracted towards them.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] As mentioned previously, francium is expected to be an exception.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Because of the higher electronegativity of lithium, some of its compounds have a more covalent character.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] For example, lithium iodide (LiI) will dissolve in organic solvents, a property of most covalent compounds.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Lithium fluoride (LiF) is the only alkali halide that is not soluble in water, and lithium hydroxide (LiOH) is the only alkali metal hydroxide that is not deliquescent.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The melting point of a substance is the point where it changes state from solid to liquid while the boiling point of a substance (in liquid state) is the point where the vapour pressure of the liquid equals the environmental pressure surrounding the liquid and all the liquid changes state to gas.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] As a metal is heated to its melting point, the metallic bonds keeping the atoms in place weaken so that the atoms can move around, and the metallic bonds eventually break completely at the metal's boiling point.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Therefore, the falling melting and boiling points of the alkali metals indicate that the strength of the metallic bonds of the alkali metals decreases down the group.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] This is because metal atoms are held together by the electromagnetic attraction from the positive ions to the delocalised electrons.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The increased nuclear charge is not a relevant factor due to the shielding effect.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The alkali metals all have the same crystal structure (body-centred cubic) and thus the only relevant factors are the number of atoms that can fit into a certain volume and the mass of one of the atoms, since density is defined as mass per unit volume.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The first factor depends on the volume of the atom and thus the atomic radius, which increases going down the group; thus, the volume of an alkali metal atom increases going down the group.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The mass of an alkali metal atom also increases going down the group.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Thus, the trend for the densities of the alkali metals depends on their atomic weights and atomic radii; if figures for these two factors are known, the ratios between the densities of the alkali metals can then be calculated.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] The resultant trend is that the densities of the alkali metals increase down the table, with an exception at potassium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Due to having the lowest atomic weight and the largest atomic radius of all the elements in their periods, the alkali metals are the least dense metals in the periodic table.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p01] Lithium, sodium, and potassium are the only three metals in the periodic table that are less dense than water: in fact, lithium is the least dense known solid at room temperature.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metals form complete series of compounds with all usually encountered anions, which well illustrate group trends.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] These compounds can be described as involving the alkali metals losing electrons to acceptor species and forming monopositive ions.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] This description is most accurate for alkali halides and becomes less and less accurate as cationic and anionic charge increase, and as the anion becomes larger and more polarisable.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] For instance, ionic bonding gives way to metallic bonding along the series NaCl, Na2O, Na2S, Na3P, Na3As, Na3Sb, Na3Bi, Na.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] All the alkali metals react vigorously or explosively with cold water, producing an aqueous solution of a strongly basic alkali metal hydroxide and releasing hydrogen gas.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] This reaction becomes more vigorous going down the group: lithium reacts steadily with effervescence, but sodium and potassium can ignite, and rubidium and caesium sink in water and generate hydrogen gas so rapidly that shock waves form in the water that may shatter glass containers.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] When an alkali metal is dropped into water, it produces an explosion, of which there are two separate stages.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The metal reacts with the water first, breaking the hydrogen bonds in the water and producing hydrogen gas; this takes place faster for the more reactive heavier alkali metals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Second, the heat generated by the first part of the reaction often ignites the hydrogen gas, causing it to burn explosively into the surrounding air.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] This secondary hydrogen gas explosion produces the visible flame above the bowl of water, lake or other body of water, not the initial reaction of the metal with water (which tends to happen mostly under water).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metal hydroxides are the most basic known hydroxides.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Recent research has suggested that the explosive behavior of alkali metals in water is driven by a Coulomb explosion rather than solely by rapid generation of hydrogen itself.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] All alkali metals melt as a part of the reaction with water.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Water molecules ionise the bare metallic surface of the liquid metal, leaving a positively charged metal surface and negatively charged water ions.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The attraction between the charged metal and water ions will rapidly increase the surface area, causing an exponential increase of ionisation.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] When the repulsive forces within the liquid metal surface exceeds the forces of the surface tension, it vigorously explodes.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The hydroxides themselves are the most basic hydroxides known, reacting with acids to give salts and with alcohols to give oligomeric alkoxides.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] They easily react with carbon dioxide to form carbonates or bicarbonates, or with hydrogen sulfide to form sulfides or bisulfides, and may be used to separate thiols from petroleum.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] They react with amphoteric oxides: for example, the oxides of aluminium, zinc, tin, and lead react with the alkali metal hydroxides to give aluminates, zincates, stannates, and plumbates.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Silicon dioxide is acidic, and thus the alkali metal hydroxides can also attack silicate glass.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metals form many intermetallic compounds with each other and the elements from groups 2 to 13 in the periodic table of varying stoichiometries, such as the sodium amalgams with mercury, including Na5Hg8 and Na3Hg.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Some of these have ionic characteristics: taking the alloys with gold, the most electronegative of metals, as an example, NaAu and KAu are metallic, but RbAu and CsAu are semiconductors.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] NaK is an alloy of sodium and potassium that is very useful because it is liquid at room temperature, although precautions must be taken due to its extreme reactivity towards water and air.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] An alloy of 41% caesium, 47% sodium, and 12% potassium has the lowest known melting point of any metal or alloy, −78 °C.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Nevertheless, while the elements in group 14 and beyond tend to form discrete anionic clusters, group 13 elements tend to form polymeric ions with the alkali metal cations located between the giant ionic lattice.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] For example, NaTl consists of a polymeric anion (—Tl−—)n with a covalent diamond cubic structure with Na+ ions located between the anionic lattice.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The larger alkali metals cannot fit similarly into an anionic lattice and tend to force the heavier group 13 elements to form anionic clusters.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Boron is a special case, being the only nonmetal in group 13.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metal borides tend to be boron-rich, involving appreciable boron–boron bonding involving deltahedral structures, and are thermally unstable due to the alkali metals having a very high vapour pressure at elevated temperatures.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] This makes direct synthesis problematic because the alkali metals do not react with boron below 700 °C, and thus this must be accomplished in sealed containers with the alkali metal in excess.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Furthermore, exceptionally in this group, reactivity with boron decreases down the group: lithium reacts completely at 700 °C, but sodium at 900 °C and potassium not until 1200 °C, and the reaction is instantaneous for lithium but takes hours for potassium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Rubidium and caesium borides have not even been characterised.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Various phases are known, such as LiB10, NaB6, NaB15, and KB6.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Under high pressure the boron–boron bonding in the lithium borides changes from following Wade's rules to forming Zintl anions like the rest of group 13.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Lithium and sodium react with carbon to form acetylides, Li2C2 and Na2C2, which can also be obtained by reaction of the metal with acetylene.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] These compounds are over 200 times more electrically conductive than pure graphite, suggesting that the valence electron of the alkali metal is transferred to the graphite layers (e.g.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Upon heating of KC8, the elimination of potassium atoms results in the conversion in sequence to KC24, KC36, KC48 and finally KC60.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] KC8 is a very strong reducing agent and is pyrophoric and explodes on contact with water.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] While the larger alkali metals (K, Rb, and Cs) initially form MC8, the smaller ones initially form MC6, and indeed they require reaction of the metals with graphite at high temperatures around 500 °C to form.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Apart from this, the alkali metals are such strong reducing agents that they can even reduce buckminsterfullerene to produce solid fullerides M*n*C60; sodium, potassium, rubidium, and caesium can form fullerides where *n* = 2, 3, 4, or 6, and rubidium and caesium additionally can achieve *n* = 1.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] When the alkali metals react with the heavier elements in the carbon group (silicon, germanium, tin, and lead), ionic substances with cage-like structures are formed, such as the silicides M4Si4 (M = K, Rb, or Cs), which contains M+ and tetrahedral Si4−4 ions.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The chemistry of alkali metal germanides, involving the germanide ion Ge4− and other cluster (Zintl) ions such as Ge2−4, Ge4−9, Ge2−9, and [(Ge9)2]6−, is largely analogous to that of the corresponding silicides.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Alkali metal stannides are mostly ionic, sometimes with the stannide ion (Sn4−), and sometimes with more complex Zintl ions such as Sn4−9, which appears in tetrapotassium nonastannide (K4Sn9).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The monatomic plumbide ion (Pb4−) is unknown, and indeed its formation is predicted to be energetically unfavourable; alkali metal plumbides have complex Zintl ions, such as Pb4−9.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] These alkali metal germanides, stannides, and plumbides may be produced by reducing germanium, tin, and lead with sodium metal in liquid ammonia.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Lithium, the lightest of the alkali metals, is the only alkali metal which reacts with nitrogen at standard conditions, and its nitride is the only stable alkali metal nitride.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Nitrogen is an unreactive gas because breaking the strong triple bond in the dinitrogen molecule (N2) requires a lot of energy.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The reactions of the other alkali metals with nitrogen would not release enough lattice energy and would thus be endothermic, so they do not form nitrides at standard conditions.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Sodium nitride (Na3N) and potassium nitride (K3N), while existing, are extremely unstable, being prone to decomposing back into their constituent elements, and cannot be produced by reacting the elements with each other at standard conditions.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Steric hindrance forbids the existence of rubidium or caesium nitride.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] However, sodium and potassium form colourless azide salts involving the linear N−3 anion; due to the large size of the alkali metal cations, they are thermally stable enough to be able to melt before decomposing.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] All the alkali metals react readily with phosphorus and arsenic to form phosphides and arsenides with the formula M3Pn (where M represents an alkali metal and Pn represents a pnictogen – phosphorus, arsenic, antimony, or bismuth).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] This is due to the greater size of the P3− and As3− ions, so that less lattice energy needs to be released for the salts to form.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] These are not the only phosphides and arsenides of the alkali metals: for example, potassium has nine different known phosphides, with formulae K3P, K4P3, K5P4, KP, K4P6, K3P7, K3P11, KP10.3, and KP15.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] While most metals form arsenides, only the alkali and alkaline earth metals form mostly ionic arsenides.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The structure of Na3As is complex with unusually short Na–Na distances of 328–330 pm which are shorter than in sodium metal, and this indicates that even with these electropositive metals the bonding cannot be straightforwardly ionic.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Other alkali metal arsenides not conforming to the formula M3As are known, such as LiAs, which has a metallic lustre and electrical conductivity indicating the presence of some metallic bonding.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The antimonides are unstable and reactive as the Sb3− ion is a strong reducing agent; reaction of them with acids form the toxic and unstable gas stibine (SbH3).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Indeed, they have some metallic properties, and the alkali metal antimonides of stoichiometry MSb involve antimony atoms bonded in a spiral Zintl structure.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Bismuthides are not even wholly ionic; they are intermetallic compounds containing partially metallic and partially ionic bonds.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] cluster, composed of three regular octahedra where each octahedron is connected to both of the others by one face each.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] All three octahedra have one edge in common.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] All the alkali metals react vigorously with oxygen at standard conditions.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] They form various types of oxides, such as simple oxides (containing the O2− ion), peroxides (containing the O2−2 ion, where there is a single bond between the two oxygen atoms), superoxides (containing the O−2 ion), and many others.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Lithium burns in air to form lithium oxide, but sodium reacts with oxygen to form a mixture of sodium oxide and sodium peroxide.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Potassium forms a mixture of potassium peroxide and potassium superoxide, while rubidium and caesium form the superoxide exclusively.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Their reactivity increases going down the group: while lithium, sodium and potassium merely burn in air, rubidium and caesium are pyrophoric (spontaneously catch fire in air).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The smaller alkali metals tend to polarise the larger anions (the peroxide and superoxide) due to their small size.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] This attracts the electrons in the more complex anions towards one of its constituent oxygen atoms, forming an oxide ion and an oxygen atom.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] This causes lithium to form the oxide exclusively on reaction with oxygen at room temperature.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] This effect becomes drastically weaker for the larger sodium and potassium, allowing them to form the less stable peroxides.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Rubidium and caesium, at the bottom of the group, are so large that even the least stable superoxides can form.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Because the superoxide releases the most energy when formed, the superoxide is preferentially formed for the larger alkali metals where the more complex anions are not polarised.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The oxides and peroxides for these alkali metals do exist, but do not form upon direct reaction of the metal with oxygen at standard conditions.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] In addition, the small size of the Li+ and O2− ions contributes to their forming a stable ionic lattice structure.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Under controlled conditions, however, all the alkali metals, with the exception of francium, are known to form their oxides, peroxides, and superoxides.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metal peroxides and superoxides are powerful oxidising agents.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] All the stable alkali metals except lithium can form red ozonides (MO3) through low-temperature reaction of the powdered anhydrous hydroxide with ozone: the ozonides may be then extracted using liquid ammonia.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] They slowly decompose at standard conditions to the superoxides and oxygen, and hydrolyse immediately to the hydroxides when in contact with water.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Potassium, rubidium, and caesium also form sesquioxides M2O3, which may be better considered peroxide disuperoxides, [(M+)4(O2−2)(O−2)2].
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Rubidium and caesium can form a great variety of suboxides with the metals in formal oxidation states below +1.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Rubidium can form Rb6O and Rb9O2 (copper-coloured) upon oxidation in air, while caesium forms an immense variety of oxides, such as the ozonide CsO3 and several brightly coloured suboxides, such as Cs7O (bronze), Cs4O (red-violet), Cs11O3 (violet), Cs3O (dark green), CsO, Cs3O2, as well as Cs7O2.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The last of these may be heated under vacuum to generate Cs2O.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metals can also react analogously with the heavier chalcogens (sulfur, selenium, tellurium, and polonium), and all the alkali metal chalcogenides are known (with the exception of francium's).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Reaction with an excess of the chalcogen can similarly result in lower chalcogenides, with chalcogen ions containing chains of the chalcogen atoms in question.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] For example, sodium can react with sulfur to form the sulfide (Na2S) and various polysulfides with the formula Na2S*x* (*x* from 2 to 6), containing the S2− *x* ions.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Due to the basicity of the Se2− and Te2− ions, the alkali metal selenides and tellurides are alkaline in solution; when reacted directly with selenium and tellurium, alkali metal polyselenides and polytellurides are formed along with the selenides and tellurides with the Se2− *x* and Te2− *x* ions.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] They may be obtained directly from the elements in liquid ammonia or when air is not present, and are colourless, water-soluble compounds that air oxidises quickly back to selenium or tellurium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metal polonides are all ionic compounds containing the Po2− ion; they are very chemically stable and can be produced by direct reaction of the elements at around 300–400 °C.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metals are among the most electropositive elements on the periodic table and thus tend to bond ionically to the most electronegative elements on the periodic table, the halogens (fluorine, chlorine, bromine, iodine, and astatine), forming salts known as the alkali metal halides.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The reaction is very vigorous and can sometimes result in explosions.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] All twenty stable alkali metal halides are known; the unstable ones are not known, with the exception of sodium astatide, because of the great instability and rarity of astatine and francium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The most well-known of the twenty is certainly sodium chloride, otherwise known as common salt.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] All of the stable alkali metal halides have the formula MX where M is an alkali metal and X is a halogen.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] They are all white ionic crystalline solids that have high melting points.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] All the alkali metal halides are soluble in water except for lithium fluoride (LiF), which is insoluble in water due to its very high lattice enthalpy.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The high lattice enthalpy of lithium fluoride is due to the small sizes of the Li+ and F− ions, causing the electrostatic interactions between them to be strong: a similar effect occurs for magnesium fluoride, consistent with the diagonal relationship between lithium and magnesium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metals also react similarly with hydrogen to form ionic alkali metal hydrides, where the hydride anion acts as a pseudohalide: these are often used as reducing agents, producing hydrides, complex metal hydrides, or hydrogen gas.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Other pseudohalides are also known, notably the cyanides.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] These are isostructural to the respective halides except for lithium cyanide, indicating that the cyanide ions may rotate freely.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Ternary alkali metal halide oxides, such as Na3ClO, K3BrO (yellow), Na4Br2O, Na4I2O, and K4Br2O, are also known.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The polyhalides are rather unstable, although those of rubidium and caesium are greatly stabilised by the feeble polarising power of these extremely large cations.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] encapsulating a potassium cation (purple).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] At crystalline state, obtained with an X-ray diffraction.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Alkali metal cations do not usually form coordination complexes with simple Lewis bases due to their low charge of just +1 and their relatively large size; thus the Li+ ion forms most complexes and the heavier alkali metal ions form less and less (though exceptions occur for weak complexes).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Lithium in particular has a very rich coordination chemistry in which it exhibits coordination numbers from 1 to 12, although octahedral hexacoordination is its preferred mode.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Because of this, anhydrous salts containing alkali metal cations are often used as desiccants.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Alkali metals also readily form complexes with crown ethers (e.g.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] 12-crown-4 for Li+, 15-crown-5 for Na+, 18-crown-6 for K+, and 21-crown-7 for Rb+) and cryptands due to electrostatic attraction.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The process may be speeded up by a catalyst.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Similar solutions are formed by the heavy divalent alkaline earth metals calcium, strontium, barium, as well as the divalent lanthanides, europium and ytterbium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The amide salt is quite insoluble and readily precipitates out of solution, leaving intensely coloured ammonia solutions of the alkali metals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Kraus identified the colour as being due to the presence of solvated electrons, which contribute to the high electrical conductivity of these solutions.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] At low concentrations (below 3 M), the solution is dark blue and has ten times the conductivity of aqueous sodium chloride; at higher concentrations (above 3 M), the solution is copper-coloured and has approximately the conductivity of liquid metals like mercury.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] In addition to the alkali metal amide salt and solvated electrons, such ammonia solutions also contain the alkali metal cation (M+), the neutral alkali metal atom (M), diatomic alkali metal molecules (M2) and alkali metal anions (M−).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] These are unstable and eventually become the more thermodynamically stable alkali metal amide and hydrogen gas.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Solvated electrons are powerful reducing agents and are often used in chemical synthesis.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Being the smallest alkali metal, lithium forms the widest variety of and most stable organometallic compounds, which are bonded covalently.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Organolithium compounds are electrically non-conducting volatile solids or liquids that melt at low temperatures, and tend to form oligomers with the structure (RLi)*x* where R is the organic group.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] As the electropositive nature of lithium puts most of the charge density of the bond on the carbon atom, effectively creating a carbanion, organolithium compounds are extremely powerful bases and nucleophiles.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] For use as bases, butyllithiums are often used and are commercially available.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] An example of an organolithium compound is methyllithium ((CH3Li)*x*), which exists in tetrameric (*x* = 4, tetrahedral) and hexameric (*x* = 6, octahedral) forms.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Organolithium compounds, especially *n*-butyllithium, are useful reagents in organic synthesis, as might be expected given lithium's diagonal relationship with magnesium, which plays an important role in the Grignard reaction.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] For example, alkyllithiums and aryllithiums may be used to synthesise aldehydes and ketones by reaction with metal carbonyls.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The reaction with nickel tetracarbonyl, for example, proceeds through an unstable acyl nickel carbonyl complex which then undergoes electrophilic substitution to give the desired aldehyde (using H+ as the electrophile) or ketone (using an alkyl halide) product.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Alkyllithiums and aryllithiums may also react with *N*,*N*-disubstituted amides to give aldehydes and ketones, and symmetrical ketones by reacting with carbon monoxide.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] They thermally decompose to eliminate a β-hydrogen, producing alkenes and lithium hydride: another route is the reaction of ethers with alkyl- and aryllithiums that act as strong bases.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] In non-polar solvents, aryllithiums react as the carbanions they effectively are, turning carbon dioxide to aromatic carboxylic acids (ArCO2H) and aryl ketones to tertiary carbinols (Ar'2C(Ar)OH).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Finally, they may be used to synthesise other organometallic compounds through metal-halogen exchange.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Unlike the organolithium compounds, the organometallic compounds of the heavier alkali metals are predominantly ionic.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The application of organosodium compounds in chemistry is limited in part due to competition from organolithium compounds, which are commercially available and exhibit more convenient reactivity.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The principal organosodium compound of commercial importance is sodium cyclopentadienide.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Sodium tetraphenylborate can also be classified as an organosodium compound since in the solid state sodium is bound to the aryl groups.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Organometallic compounds of the higher alkali metals are even more reactive than organosodium compounds and of limited utility.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] A notable reagent is Schlosser's base, a mixture of *n*-butyllithium and potassium *tert*-butoxide.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] This reagent reacts with propene to form the compound allylpotassium (KCH2CHCH2).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] *cis*-2-Butene and *trans*-2-butene equilibrate when in contact with alkali metals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Whereas isomerisation is fast with lithium and sodium, it is slow with the heavier alkali metals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The heavier alkali metals also favour the sterically congested conformation.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Several crystal structures of organopotassium compounds have been reported, establishing that they, like the sodium compounds, are polymeric.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Organosodium, organopotassium, organorubidium and organocaesium compounds are all mostly ionic and are insoluble (or nearly so) in nonpolar solvents.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Alkyl and aryl derivatives of sodium and potassium tend to react with air.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] They cause the cleavage of ethers, generating alkoxides.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] As such, they have to be made by reacting alkylmercury compounds with sodium or potassium metal in inert hydrocarbon solvents.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] While methylsodium forms tetramers like methyllithium, methylpotassium is more ionic and has the nickel arsenide structure with discrete methyl anions and potassium cations.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metals and their hydrides react with acidic hydrocarbons, for example cyclopentadienes and terminal alkynes, to give salts.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Liquid ammonia, ether, or hydrocarbon solvents are used, the most common of which being tetrahydrofuran.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The most important of these compounds is sodium cyclopentadienide, NaC5H5, an important precursor to many transition metal cyclopentadienyl derivatives.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Similarly, the alkali metals react with cyclooctatetraene in tetrahydrofuran to give alkali metal cyclooctatetraenides; for example, dipotassium cyclooctatetraenide (K2C8H8) is an important precursor to many metal cyclooctatetraenyl derivatives, such as uranocene.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The large and very weakly polarising alkali metal cations can stabilise large, aromatic, polarisable radical anions, such as the dark-green sodium naphthalenide, Na+[C10H8•]−, a strong reducing agent.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Upon reacting with oxygen, alkali metals form oxides, peroxides, superoxides and suboxides.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] However, the first three are more common.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The table below shows the types of compounds formed in reaction with oxygen.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The compound in brackets represents the minor product of combustion.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metal peroxides are ionic compounds that are unstable in water.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The peroxide anion is weakly bound to the cation, and it is hydrolysed, forming stronger covalent bonds.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The other oxygen compounds are also unstable in water.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] With sulfur, they form sulfides and polysulfides.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Because alkali metal sulfides are essentially salts of a weak acid and a strong base, they form basic solutions.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Lithium is the only metal that combines directly with nitrogen at room temperature.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Li3N can react with water to liberate ammonia.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] With hydrogen, alkali metals form saline hydrides that hydrolyse in water.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Lithium is the only metal that reacts directly with carbon to give dilithium acetylide.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Na and K can react with acetylene to give acetylides.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] On reaction with water, they generate hydroxide ions and hydrogen gas.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] This reaction is vigorous and highly exothermic and the hydrogen resulted may ignite in air or even explode in the case of Rb and Cs.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metals are very good reducing agents.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] They can reduce metal cations that are less electropositive.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Titanium is produced industrially by the reduction of titanium tetrachloride with Na at 400 °C (van Arkel–de Boer process).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Alkali metals react with halogen derivatives to generate hydrocarbon via the Wurtz reaction.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Alkali metals dissolve in liquid ammonia or other donor solvents like aliphatic amines or hexamethylphosphoramide to give blue solutions.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] These solutions are believed to contain free electrons.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Due to the presence of solvated electrons, these solutions are very powerful reducing agents used in organic synthesis.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Reaction 1) is known as Birch reduction.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Although francium is the heaviest alkali metal that has been discovered, there has been some theoretical work predicting the physical and chemical characteristics of hypothetical heavier alkali metals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Being the first period 8 element, the undiscovered element ununennium (element 119) is predicted to be the next alkali metal after francium and behave much like their lighter congeners; however, it is also predicted to differ from the lighter alkali metals in some properties.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Its chemistry is predicted to be closer to that of potassium or rubidium instead of caesium or francium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] This is unusual as periodic trends, ignoring relativistic effects would predict ununennium to be even more reactive than caesium and francium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] This lowered reactivity is due to the relativistic stabilisation of ununennium's valence electron, increasing ununennium's first ionisation energy and decreasing the metallic and ionic radii; this effect is already seen for francium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] This assumes that ununennium will behave chemically as an alkali metal, which, although likely, may not be true due to relativistic effects.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The relativistic stabilisation of the 8s orbital also increases ununennium's electron affinity far beyond that of caesium and francium; indeed, ununennium is expected to have an electron affinity higher than all the alkali metals lighter than it.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Relativistic effects also cause a very large drop in the polarisability of ununennium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] On the other hand, ununennium is predicted to continue the trend of melting points decreasing going down the group, being expected to have a melting point between 0 °C and 30 °C.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] On the other hand, the ionic radius of the Uue+ ion is predicted to be larger than that of Rb+, because the 7p orbitals are destabilised and are thus larger than the p-orbitals of the lower shells.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Indeed, many ununennium compounds are expected to have a large covalent character, due to the involvement of the 7p3/2 electrons in the bonding.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Not as much work has been done predicting the properties of the alkali metals beyond ununennium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] This element would be intermediate in properties between an alkali metal and a group 11 element, and while its physical and atomic properties would be closer to the former, its chemistry may be closer to that of the latter.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] However, the 7d electrons of unhexpentium may also be able to participate in chemical reactions along with the 9s electron, possibly allowing oxidation states beyond +1, whence the likely transition metal behaviour of unhexpentium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Due to the alkali and alkaline earth metals both being s-block elements, these predictions for the trends and properties of ununennium and unhexpentium also mostly hold quite similarly for the corresponding alkaline earth metals unbinilium (Ubn) and unhexhexium (Uhh).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] The probable properties of further alkali metals beyond unsepttrium have not been explored yet as of 2019, and they may or may not be able to exist.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] In periods 8 and above of the periodic table, relativistic and shell-structure effects become so strong that extrapolations from lighter congeners become completely inaccurate.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p02] Interest in the chemical properties of ununennium, unhexpentium, and unsepttrium stems from the fact that they are located close to the expected locations of islands of stability, centered at elements 122 (306Ubb) and 164 (482Uhq).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Many other substances are similar to the alkali metals in their tendency to form monopositive cations.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Analogously to the pseudohalogens, they have sometimes been called "pseudo-alkali metals".
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] These substances include some elements and many more polyatomic ions; the polyatomic ions are especially similar to the alkali metals in their large size and weak polarising power.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] The element hydrogen, with one electron per neutral atom, is usually placed at the top of Group 1 of the periodic table because of its electron configuration.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] But hydrogen is not normally considered to be an alkali metal.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Metallic hydrogen, which only exists at very high pressures, is known for its electrical and magnetic properties, not its chemical properties.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Under typical conditions, pure hydrogen exists as a diatomic gas consisting of two atoms per molecule (H2); however, the alkali metals form diatomic molecules (such as dilithium, Li2) only at high temperatures, when they are in the gaseous state.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Hydrogen, like the alkali metals, has one valence electron and reacts easily with the halogens, but the similarities mostly end there because of the small size of a bare proton H+ compared to the alkali metal cations.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Its placement above lithium is primarily due to its electron configuration.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] It is sometimes placed above fluorine due to their similar chemical properties, though the resemblance is likewise not absolute.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] The first ionisation energy of hydrogen (1312.0 kJ/mol) is much higher than that of the alkali metals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] As only one additional electron is required to fill in the outermost shell of the hydrogen atom, hydrogen often behaves like a halogen, forming the negative hydride ion, and is very occasionally considered to be a halogen on that basis.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] (The alkali metals can also form negative ions, known as alkalides, but these are little more than laboratory curiosities, being unstable.) An argument against this placement is that formation of hydride from hydrogen is endothermic, unlike the exothermic formation of halides from halogens.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] The radius of the H− anion also does not fit the trend of increasing size going down the halogens: indeed, H− is very diffuse because its single proton cannot easily control both electrons.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] The electrical resistivity of liquid metallic hydrogen at 3000 K is approximately equal to that of liquid rubidium and caesium at 2000 K at the respective pressures when they undergo a nonmetal-to-metal transition.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] The 1s1 electron configuration of hydrogen, while analogous to that of the alkali metals (ns1), is unique because there is no 1p subshell.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Hence it can lose an electron to form the hydron H+, or gain one to form the hydride ion H−.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] In the former case it resembles superficially the alkali metals; in the latter case, the halogens, but the differences due to the lack of a 1p subshell are important enough that neither group fits the properties of hydrogen well.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Group 14 is also a good fit in terms of thermodynamic properties such as ionisation energy and electron affinity, but hydrogen cannot be tetravalent.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Indeed, transferring of protons between chemicals is the basis of acid-base chemistry.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Also unique is hydrogen's ability to form hydrogen bonds, which are an effect of charge-transfer, electrostatic, and electron correlative contributing phenomena.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] While analogous lithium bonds are also known, they are mostly electrostatic.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Nevertheless, hydrogen can take on the same structural role as the alkali metals in some molecular crystals, and has a close relationship with the lightest alkali metals (especially lithium).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] The ammonium ion (NH+4) has very similar properties to the heavier alkali metals, acting as an alkali metal intermediate between potassium and rubidium, and is often considered a close relative.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] For example, most alkali metal salts are soluble in water, a property which ammonium salts share.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] It has been estimated that the transition from a mixture of ammonia and dihydrogen molecules to metallic ammonium may occur at pressures just below 25 GPa.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Under standard conditions, ammonium can form a metallic amalgam with mercury.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Other "pseudo-alkali metals" include the alkylammonium cations, in which some of the hydrogen atoms in the ammonium cation are replaced by alkyl or aryl groups.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] In particular, the quaternary ammonium cations (NR+4) are very useful since they are permanently charged, and they are often used as an alternative to the expensive Cs+ to stabilise very large and very easily polarisable anions such as HI−2.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Tetraalkylammonium hydroxides, like alkali metal hydroxides, are very strong bases that react with atmospheric carbon dioxide to form carbonates.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Cobaltocene, Co(C5H5)2, is a metallocene, the cobalt analogue of ferrocene.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Cobaltocene has 19 valence electrons, one more than usually found in organotransition metal complexes, such as its very stable relative, ferrocene, in accordance with the 18-electron rule.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] This additional electron occupies an orbital that is antibonding with respect to the Co–C bonds.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Consequently, many chemical reactions of Co(C5H5)2 are characterized by its tendency to lose this "extra" electron, yielding a very stable 18-electron cation known as cobaltocenium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Many cobaltocenium salts coprecipitate with caesium salts, and cobaltocenium hydroxide is a strong base that absorbs atmospheric carbon dioxide to form cobaltocenium carbonate.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Like the alkali metals, cobaltocene is a strong reducing agent, and decamethylcobaltocene is stronger still due to the combined inductive effect of the ten methyl groups.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Cobalt may be substituted by its heavier congener rhodium to give rhodocene, an even stronger reducing agent.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Iridocene (involving iridium) would presumably be still more potent, but is not very well-studied due to its instability.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Thallium is the heaviest stable element in group 13 of the periodic table.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] It was sometimes considered an alkali metal in continental Europe (but not in England) in the years immediately following its discovery, and was placed just after caesium as the sixth alkali metal in Dmitri Mendeleev's 1869 periodic table and Julius Lothar Meyer's 1868 periodic table.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Mendeleev's 1871 periodic table and Meyer's 1870 periodic table put thallium in its current position in the boron group and left the space below caesium blank.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] However, thallium also displays the oxidation state +3, which no known alkali metal displays (although ununennium, the undiscovered seventh alkali metal, is predicted to possibly display the +3 oxidation state).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] The sixth alkali metal is now considered to be francium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] While Tl+ is stabilised by the inert-pair effect, this inert pair of 6s electrons is still able to participate chemically, so that these electrons are stereochemically active in aqueous solution.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Additionally, the thallium halides (except TlF) are quite insoluble in water, and TlI has an unusual structure because of the presence of the stereochemically active inert pair in thallium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] The group 11 metals (or coinage metals), copper, silver, and gold, are typically categorised as transition metals given they can form ions with incomplete d-shells.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Physically, they have the relatively low melting points and high electronegativity values associated with post-transition metals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] "The filled *d* subshell and free *s* electron of Cu, Ag, and Au contribute to their high electrical and thermal conductivity.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] They are occasionally classified as post-transition metals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Their spectra are analogous to those of the alkali metals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Their monopositive ions are paramagnetic and contribute no colour to their salts, like those of the alkali metals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] In Mendeleev's 1871 periodic table, copper, silver, and gold are listed twice, once under group VIII (with the iron triad and platinum group metals), and once under group IB.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Group IB was nonetheless parenthesised to note that it was tentative.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Mendeleev's main criterion for group assignment was the maximum oxidation state of an element: on that basis, the group 11 elements could not be classified in group IB, due to the existence of copper(II) and gold(III) compounds being known at that time.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] However, eliminating group IB would make group I the only main group (group VIII was labelled a transition group) to lack an A–B bifurcation.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] The coinage metals were traditionally regarded as a subdivision of the alkali metal group, due to them sharing the characteristic s1 electron configuration of the alkali metals (group 1: p6s1; group 11: d10s1).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] However, the similarities are largely confined to the stoichiometries of the +1 compounds of both groups, and not their chemical properties.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] This stems from the filled d subshell providing a much weaker shielding effect on the outermost s electron than the filled p subshell, so that the coinage metals have much higher first ionisation energies and smaller ionic radii than do the corresponding alkali metals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Furthermore, they have higher melting points, hardnesses, and densities, and lower reactivities and solubilities in liquid ammonia, as well as having more covalent character in their compounds.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Finally, the alkali metals are at the top of the electrochemical series, whereas the coinage metals are almost at the very bottom.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] The production of pure alkali metals is somewhat complicated due to their extreme reactivity with commonly used substances, such as water.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] The remaining insoluble alkali metal carbonate is then precipitated selectively; the salt is then dissolved in hydrochloric acid to produce the chloride.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] The result is then left to evaporate and the alkali metal can then be isolated.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Lithium and sodium are typically isolated through electrolysis from their liquid chlorides, with calcium chloride typically added to lower the melting point of the mixture.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] The heavier alkali metals, however, are more typically isolated in a different way, where a reducing agent (typically sodium for potassium and magnesium or calcium for the heaviest alkali metals) is used to reduce the alkali metal chloride.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] The liquid or gaseous product (the alkali metal) then undergoes fractional distillation for purification.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Most routes to the pure alkali metals require the use of electrolysis due to their high reactivity; one of the few which does not is the pyrolysis of the corresponding alkali metal azide, which yields the metal for sodium, potassium, rubidium, and caesium and the nitride for lithium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Lithium salts have to be extracted from the water of mineral springs, brine pools, and brine deposits.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] The metal is produced electrolytically from a mixture of fused lithium chloride and potassium chloride.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Sodium occurs mostly in seawater and dried seabed, but is now produced through electrolysis of sodium chloride by lowering the melting point of the substance to below 700 °C through the use of a Downs cell.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Extremely pure sodium can be produced through the thermal decomposition of sodium azide.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Potassium occurs in many minerals, such as sylvite (potassium chloride).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Previously, potassium was generally made from the electrolysis of potassium chloride or potassium hydroxide, found extensively in places such as Canada, Russia, Belarus, Germany, Israel, United States, and Jordan, in a method similar to how sodium was produced in the late 1800s and early 1900s.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] However, these methods are problematic because the potassium metal tends to dissolve in its molten chloride and vaporises significantly at the operating temperatures, potentially forming the explosive superoxide.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] As a result, pure potassium metal is now produced by reducing molten potassium chloride with sodium metal at 850 °C.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Although sodium is less reactive than potassium, this process works because at such high temperatures potassium is more volatile than sodium and can easily be distilled off, so that the equilibrium shifts towards the right to produce more potassium gas and proceeds almost to completion.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Metals like sodium are obtained by electrolysis of molten salts.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Rb & Cs obtained mainly as by products of Li processing.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] To make pure caesium, ores of caesium and rubidium are crushed and heated to 650 °C with sodium metal, generating an alloy that can then be separated via a fractional distillation technique.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Because metallic caesium is too reactive to handle, it is normally offered as caesium azide (CsN3).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Caesium hydroxide is formed when caesium interacts aggressively with water and ice (CsOH).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Rubidium is the 16th most abundant element in the earth's crust; however, it is quite rare.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Some minerals found in North America, South Africa, Russia, and Canada contain rubidium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Some potassium minerals (lepidolites, biotites, feldspar, carnallite) contain it, together with caesium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Pollucite, carnallite, leucite, and lepidolite are all minerals that contain rubidium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] As a by-product of lithium extraction, it is commercially obtained from lepidolite.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Rubidium is also found in potassium rocks and brines, which is a commercial supply.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] The majority of rubidium is now obtained as a byproduct of refining lithium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Rubidium is used in vacuum tubes as a getter, a material that combines with and removes trace gases from vacuum tubes.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] For several years in the 1950s and 1960s, a by-product of the potassium production called Alkarb was a main source for rubidium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Alkarb contained 21% rubidium while the rest was potassium and a small fraction of caesium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Today the largest producers of caesium, for example the Tanco Mine in Manitoba, Canada, produce rubidium as by-product from pollucite.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Today, a common method for separating rubidium from potassium and caesium is the fractional crystallisation of a rubidium and caesium alum (Cs, Rb)Al(SO4)2·12H2O, which yields pure rubidium alum after approximately 30 recrystallisations.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] The limited applications and the lack of a mineral rich in rubidium limit the production of rubidium compounds to 2 to 4 tonnes per year.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Caesium, however, is not produced from the above reaction.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Instead, the mining of pollucite ore is the main method of obtaining pure caesium, extracted from the ore mainly by three methods: acid digestion, alkaline decomposition, and direct reduction.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Both metals are produced as by-products of lithium production: after 1958, when interest in lithium's thermonuclear properties increased sharply, the production of rubidium and caesium also increased correspondingly.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Pure rubidium and caesium metals are produced by reducing their chlorides with calcium metal at 750 °C and low pressure.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] As a result of its extreme rarity in nature, most francium is synthesised in the nuclear reaction 197Au + 18O → 210Fr + 5 n, yielding francium-209, francium-210, and francium-211.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] The greatest quantity of francium ever assembled to date is about 300,000 neutral atoms, which were synthesised using the nuclear reaction given above.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] When the only natural isotope francium-223 is specifically required, it is produced as the alpha daughter of actinium-227, itself produced synthetically from the neutron irradiation of natural radium-226, one of the daughters of natural uranium-238.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Lithium, sodium, and potassium have many useful applications, while rubidium and caesium are very notable in academic contexts but do not have many applications yet.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Lithium is the key ingredient for a range of lithium-based batteries, and lithium oxide can help process silica.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Lithium stearate is a thickener and can be used to make lubricating greases; it is produced from lithium hydroxide, which is also used to absorb carbon dioxide in space capsules and submarines.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Lithium chloride is used as a brazing alloy for aluminium parts.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] In medicine, some lithium salts are used as mood-stabilising pharmaceuticals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Metallic lithium is used in alloys with magnesium and aluminium to give very tough and light alloys.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Sodium compounds have many applications, the most well-known being sodium chloride as table salt.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Sodium salts of fatty acids are used as soap.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Pure sodium metal also has many applications, including use in sodium-vapour lamps, which produce very efficient light compared to other types of lighting, and can help smooth the surface of other metals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Being a strong reducing agent, it is often used to reduce many other metals, such as titanium and zirconium, from their chlorides.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Furthermore, it is very useful as a heat-exchange liquid in fast breeder nuclear reactors due to its low melting point, viscosity, and cross-section towards neutron absorption.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Sodium-ion batteries may provide cheaper alternatives to their equivalent lithium-based cells.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Both sodium and potassium are commonly used as GRAS counterions to create more water-soluble and hence more bioavailable salt forms of acidic pharmaceuticals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Potassium compounds are often used as fertilisers as potassium is an important element for plant nutrition.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Potassium hydroxide is a very strong base, and is used to control the pH of various substances.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Potassium nitrate and potassium permanganate are often used as powerful oxidising agents.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Potassium superoxide is used in breathing masks, as it reacts with carbon dioxide to give potassium carbonate and oxygen gas.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Pure potassium metal is not often used, but its alloys with sodium may substitute for pure sodium in fast breeder nuclear reactors.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Rubidium and caesium are often used in atomic clocks.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Caesium atomic clocks are extraordinarily accurate; if a clock had been made at the time of the dinosaurs, it would be off by less than four seconds (after 80 million years).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] For that reason, caesium atoms are used as the definition of the second.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Rubidium ions are often used in purple fireworks, and caesium is often used in drilling fluids in the petroleum industry.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Francium has no commercial applications, but because of francium's relatively simple atomic structure, among other things, it has been used in spectroscopy experiments, leading to more information regarding energy levels and the coupling constants of the weak interaction.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Studies on the light emitted by laser-trapped francium-210 ions have provided accurate data on transitions between atomic energy levels, similar to those predicted by quantum theory.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Pure alkali metals are dangerously reactive with air and water and must be kept away from heat, fire, oxidising agents, acids, most organic compounds, halocarbons, plastics, and moisture.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] They also react with carbon dioxide and carbon tetrachloride, so that normal fire extinguishers are counterproductive when used on alkali metal fires.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Some Class D dry powder extinguishers designed for metal fires are effective, depriving the fire of oxygen and cooling the alkali metal.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Experiments are usually conducted using only small quantities of a few grams in a fume hood.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Small quantities of lithium may be disposed of by reaction with cool water, but the heavier alkali metals should be dissolved in the less reactive isopropanol.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] The alkali metals must be stored under mineral oil or an inert atmosphere.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] The inert atmosphere used may be argon or nitrogen gas, except for lithium, which reacts with nitrogen.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] The bioinorganic chemistry of the alkali metal ions has been extensively reviewed.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Solid state crystal structures have been determined for many complexes of alkali metal ions in small peptides, nucleic acid constituents, carbohydrates and ionophore complexes.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Lithium naturally only occurs in traces in biological systems and has no known biological role, but does have effects on the body when ingested.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Lithium carbonate is used as a mood stabiliser in psychiatry to treat bipolar disorder (manic-depression) in daily doses of about 0.5 to 2 grams, although there are side-effects.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Excessive ingestion of lithium causes drowsiness, slurred speech and vomiting, among other symptoms, and poisons the central nervous system, which is dangerous as the required dosage of lithium to treat bipolar disorder is only slightly lower than the toxic dosage.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Its biochemistry, the way it is handled by the human body and studies using rats and goats suggest that it is an essential trace element, although the natural biological function of lithium in humans has yet to be identified.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Sodium and potassium occur in all known biological systems, generally functioning as electrolytes inside and outside cells.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Sodium is an essential nutrient that regulates blood volume, blood pressure, osmotic equilibrium and pH; the minimum physiological requirement for sodium is 500 milligrams per day.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Sodium chloride (also known as common salt) is the principal source of sodium in the diet, and is used as seasoning and preservative, such as for pickling and jerky; most of it comes from processed foods.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] The Dietary Reference Intake for sodium is 1.5 grams per day, but most people in the United States consume more than 2.3 grams per day, the minimum amount that promotes hypertension; this in turn causes 7.6 million premature deaths worldwide.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Potassium is the major cation (positive ion) inside animal cells, while sodium is the major cation outside animal cells.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] The concentration differences of these charged particles causes a difference in electric potential between the inside and outside of cells, known as the membrane potential.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] The balance between potassium and sodium is maintained by ion transporter proteins in the cell membrane.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] The cell membrane potential created by potassium and sodium ions allows the cell to generate an action potential—a "spike" of electrical discharge.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] The ability of cells to produce electrical discharge is critical for body functions such as neurotransmission, muscle contraction, and heart function.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Disruption of this balance may thus be fatal: for example, ingestion of large amounts of potassium compounds can lead to hyperkalemia strongly influencing the cardiovascular system.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Potassium chloride is used in the United States for lethal injection executions.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Due to their similar atomic radii, rubidium and caesium in the body mimic potassium and are taken up similarly.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Rubidium has no known biological role, but may help stimulate metabolism, and, similarly to caesium, replace potassium in the body causing potassium deficiency.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Partial substitution is quite possible and rather non-toxic: a 70 kg person contains on average 0.36 g of rubidium, and an increase in this value by 50 to 100 times did not show negative effects in test persons.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Rats can survive up to 50% substitution of potassium by rubidium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Rubidium (and to a much lesser extent caesium) can function as temporary cures for hypokalemia; while rubidium can adequately physiologically substitute potassium in some systems, caesium is never able to do so.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] There is only very limited evidence in the form of deficiency symptoms for rubidium being possibly essential in goats; even if this is true, the trace amounts usually present in food are more than enough.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Caesium compounds are rarely encountered by most people, but most caesium compounds are mildly toxic.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Like rubidium, caesium tends to substitute potassium in the body, but is significantly larger and is therefore a poorer substitute.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Excess caesium can lead to hypokalemia, arrhythmia, and acute cardiac arrest, but such amounts would not ordinarily be encountered in natural sources.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] As such, caesium is not a major chemical environmental pollutant.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] The median lethal dose (LD50) value for caesium chloride in mice is 2.3 g per kilogram, which is comparable to the LD50 values of potassium chloride and sodium chloride.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Caesium chloride has been promoted as an alternative cancer therapy, but has been linked to the deaths of over 50 patients, on whom it was used as part of a scientifically unvalidated cancer treatment.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Radioisotopes of caesium require special precautions: the improper handling of caesium-137 gamma ray sources can lead to release of this radioisotope and radiation injuries.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Perhaps the best-known case is the Goiânia accident of 1987, in which an improperly-disposed-of radiation therapy system from an abandoned clinic in the city of Goiânia, Brazil, was scavenged from a junkyard, and the glowing caesium salt sold to curious, uneducated buyers.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] This led to four deaths and serious injuries from radiation exposure.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Together with caesium-134, iodine-131, and strontium-90, caesium-137 was among the isotopes distributed by the Chernobyl disaster which constitute the greatest risk to health.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkali-metal-p03] Radioisotopes of francium would presumably be dangerous as well due to their high decay energy and short half-life, but none have been produced in large enough amounts to pose any serious risk.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The **alkaline earth metals** are six chemical elements in group 2 of the periodic table.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] They are beryllium (Be), magnesium (Mg), calcium (Ca), strontium (Sr), barium (Ba), and radium (Ra).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The elements have very similar properties: they are all shiny, silvery-white, somewhat reactive metals at standard temperature and pressure.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Together with helium, these elements have in common an outer s orbital which is full—that is, this orbital contains its full complement of two electrons, which the alkaline earth metals readily lose to form cations with charge +2, and an oxidation state of +2.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Helium is grouped with the noble gases and not with the alkaline earth metals, but it is theorized to have some similarities to beryllium when forced into bonding and has sometimes been suggested to belong to group 2.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] All the discovered alkaline earth metals occur in nature, although radium occurs only through the decay chain of uranium and thorium and not as a primordial element.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] There have been experiments, all unsuccessful, to try to synthesize element 120, the next potential member of the group.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The chemistry of radium is not well-established due to its radioactivity; thus, the presentation of its properties here is limited.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The alkaline earth metals are all silver-colored and soft, and have relatively low densities, melting points, and boiling points.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] In chemical terms, all of the alkaline earth metals react with the halogens to form the alkaline earth metal halides, all of which are ionic crystalline compounds (except for beryllium chloride, beryllium bromide and beryllium iodide, which are covalent).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] All the alkaline earth metals except beryllium also react with water to form strongly alkaline hydroxides and, thus, should be handled with great care.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The heavier alkaline earth metals react more vigorously than the lighter ones.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The alkaline earth metals have the second-lowest first ionization energies in their respective periods of the periodic table because of their somewhat low effective nuclear charges and the ability to attain a full outer shell configuration by losing just two electrons.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The second ionization energy of all of the alkaline metals is also somewhat low.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryllium is an exception: It does not react with water or steam unless at very high temperatures, and its halides are covalent.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] If beryllium did form compounds with an ionization state of +2, it would polarize electron clouds that are near it very strongly and would cause extensive orbital overlap, since beryllium has a high charge density.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] All compounds that include beryllium have a covalent bond.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Even the compound beryllium fluoride, which is the most ionic beryllium compound, has a low melting point and a low electrical conductivity when melted.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] All the alkaline earth metals have two electrons in their valence shell, so the energetically preferred state of achieving a filled electron shell is to lose two electrons to form doubly charged positive ions.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The alkaline earth metals all react with the halogens to form ionic halides, such as calcium chloride (CaCl 2), as well as reacting with oxygen to form oxides such as strontium oxide (SrO).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium, strontium, and barium react with water to produce hydrogen gas and their respective hydroxides (magnesium also reacts, but much more slowly), and also undergo transmetalation reactions to exchange ligands.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Isotopes of all six alkaline earth metals are present in the Earth's crust and the Solar System at varying concentrations, dependent upon the nuclides' half-lives and, hence, their nuclear stabilities.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The four underlined isotopes in the list are predicted by radionuclide decay energetics to be only observationally stable and to decay with extremely long half-lives through double-beta decay, though no decays attributed definitively to these isotopes have yet been observed as of 2024.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Radium has no stable nor primordial isotopes.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] In addition to the stable species, calcium and barium each have one extremely long-lived and primordial radionuclide: calcium-48 and barium-130, with half-lives of 5.6×1019 and 1.6×1021 years, respectively.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Both are far longer than the current age of the universe (4.7× and 117× billion times longer, respectively) and less than one part per ten billion has decayed since the formation of the Earth.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The two isotopes are stable for practical purposes.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Apart from the 21 stable or nearly-stable isotopes, the six alkaline earth elements each possess a large number of known radioisotopes.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryllium-7, beryllium-10, and calcium-41 are trace, as well as cosmogenic, nuclides, formed by the impact of cosmic rays with atmospheric or crustal atoms.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The longest half-lives among them are 1.387 million years for beryllium-10, 99.4 thousand years for calcium-41, 1599 years for radium-226 (radium's longest-lived isotope), 28.90 years for strontium-90, 10.51 years for barium-133, and 5.75 years for radium-228.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] All others have half-lives of less than half a year, most significantly shorter.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium-48 and barium-130, the two primordial and non-stable isotopes, decay only through double beta emission and have extremely long half-lives, by virtue of the extremely low probability of both beta decays occurring at the same time.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] All isotopes of radium are highly radioactive and are primarily generated through the decay of heavier radionuclides.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The longest-lived of them is radium-226, a member of the decay chain of uranium-238.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Strontium-90 and barium-140 are common fission products of uranium in nuclear reactors, accounting for 5.73% and 6.31% of uranium-235's fission products respectively when bombarded by thermal neutrons.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The two isotopes have half-lives each of 28.90 years and 12.7 days.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Strontium-90 is produced in appreciable quantities in operating nuclear reactors running on uranium-235 or plutonium-239 fuel, and a minuscule secular equilibrium concentration is also present due to rare spontaneous fission decays in naturally occurring uranium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium-48 is the lightest nuclide known to undergo double beta decay.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Naturally occurring calcium and barium are very weakly radioactive: calcium contains about 0.1874% calcium-48, and barium contains about 0.1062% barium-130.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] On average, one double-beta decay of calcium-48 will occur per second for every 90 tons of natural calcium, or 230 tons of limestone (calcium carbonate).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Through the same decay mechanism, one decay of barium-130 will occur per second for every 16,000 tons of natural barium, or 27,000 tons of baryte (barium sulfate).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The longest-lived isotope of radium is radium-226 with a half-life of 1600 years; it, along with radium-223, -224, and -228, occurs naturally in the decay chains of primordial thorium and uranium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryllium-8 is notable by its absence as it splits in half virtually instantaneously into two alpha particles whenever it is formed.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The triple alpha process in stars can only occur at energies high enough for beryllium-8 to fuse with a third alpha particle before it can decay, forming carbon-12.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] This thermonuclear rate-limiting bottleneck is the reason most main sequence stars spend billions of years fusing hydrogen within their cores, and only rarely manage to fuse carbon before collapsing into a stellar remnant, and even then merely for a timescale of ~1000 years.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The radioisotopes of alkaline earth metals tend to be "bone seekers" as they behave chemically similar to calcium, an integral component of hydroxyapatite in compact bone, and gradually accumulate in the human skeleton.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The incorporated radionuclides inflict significant damage to the bone marrow over time through the emission of ionizing radiation, primarily alpha particles.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] This property is made use of in a positive manner in the radiotherapy of certain bone cancers, since the radionuclides' chemical properties causes them to preferentially target cancerous growths in bone matter, leaving the rest of the body relatively unharmed.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Compared to their neighbors in the periodic table, alkaline earth metals tend to have a larger number of stable isotopes as they all possess an even number of protons, owing to their status as group 2 elements.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Their isotopes are generally more stable due to nucleon pairing.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] This stability is further enhanced if the isotope also has an even number of neutrons, as both kinds of nucleons can then participate in pairing and contribute to nuclei stability.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The alkaline earth metals are named after their oxides, the *alkaline earths*, whose old-fashioned names were beryllia, magnesia, lime, strontia, and baria.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] These oxides are basic (alkaline) when combined with water.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] "Earth" was a term applied by early chemists to nonmetallic substances that are insoluble in water and resistant to heating—properties shared by these oxides.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The realization that these earths were not elements but compounds is attributed to the chemist Antoine Lavoisier.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] In his *Traité Élémentaire de Chimie* (*Elements of Chemistry*) of 1789 he called them salt-forming earth elements.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Later, he suggested that the alkaline earths might be metal oxides, but admitted that this was mere conjecture.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] In 1808, acting on Lavoisier's idea, Humphry Davy became the first to obtain samples of the metals by electrolysis of their molten earths, thus supporting Lavoisier's hypothesis and causing the group to be named the *alkaline earth metals*.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The calcium compounds calcite and lime have been known and used since prehistoric times.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The same is true for the beryllium compounds beryl and emerald.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The other compounds of the alkaline earth metals were discovered starting in the early 15th century.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The magnesium compound magnesium sulfate was first discovered in 1618 by a farmer at Epsom in England.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Strontium carbonate was discovered in minerals in the Scottish village of Strontian in 1790.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The last element is the least abundant: radioactive radium, which was extracted from uraninite in 1898.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] All elements except beryllium were isolated by electrolysis of molten compounds.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Magnesium, calcium, and strontium were first produced by Humphry Davy in 1808, whereas beryllium was independently isolated by Friedrich Wöhler and Antoine Bussy in 1828 by reacting beryllium compounds with potassium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] In 1910, radium was isolated as a pure metal by Curie and André-Louis Debierne also by electrolysis.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryl, a mineral that contains beryllium, has been known since the time of the Ptolemaic Kingdom in Egypt.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Although it was originally thought that beryl was an aluminum silicate, beryl was later found to contain a then-unknown element when, in 1797, Louis-Nicolas Vauquelin dissolved aluminum hydroxide from beryl in an alkali.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] In 1828, Friedrich Wöhler and Antoine Bussy independently isolated this new element, beryllium, by the same method, which involved a reaction of beryllium chloride with metallic potassium; this reaction was not able to produce large ingots of beryllium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] It was not until 1898, when Paul Lebeau performed an electrolysis of a mixture of beryllium fluoride and sodium fluoride, that large pure samples of beryllium were produced.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Magnesium was first produced by Humphry Davy in England in 1808 using electrolysis of a mixture of magnesia and mercuric oxide.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Antoine Bussy prepared it in coherent form in 1831.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Davy's first suggestion for a name was magnium, but the name magnesium is now used.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Lime has been used as a material for building since 7000 to 14,000 BCE, and kilns used for lime have been dated to 2,500 BCE in Khafaja, Mesopotamia.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium as a material has been known since at least the first century, as the ancient Romans were known to have used calcium oxide by preparing it from lime.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium sulfate has been known to be able to set broken bones since the tenth century.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium itself, however, was not isolated until 1808, when Humphry Davy, in England, used electrolysis on a mixture of lime and mercuric oxide, after hearing that Jöns Jakob Berzelius had prepared a calcium amalgam from the electrolysis of lime in mercury.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] In 1790, physician Adair Crawford discovered ores with distinctive properties, which were named *strontites* in 1793 by Thomas Charles Hope, a chemistry professor at the University of Glasgow, who confirmed Crawford's discovery.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Strontium was eventually isolated in 1808 by Humphry Davy by electrolysis of a mixture of strontium chloride and mercuric oxide.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The discovery was announced by Davy on 30 June 1808 at a lecture to the Royal Society.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Barite, a mineral containing barium, was first recognized as containing a new element in 1774 by Carl Scheele, although he was able to isolate only barium oxide.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Barium oxide was isolated again two years later by Johan Gottlieb Gahn.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Later in the 18th century, William Withering noticed a heavy mineral in the Cumberland lead mines, which are now known to contain barium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Barium itself was finally isolated in 1808 when Humphry Davy used electrolysis with molten salts, and Davy named the element *barium*, after baryta.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Later, Robert Bunsen and Augustus Matthiessen isolated pure barium by electrolysis of a mixture of barium chloride and ammonium chloride.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] While studying uraninite, on 21 December 1898, Marie and Pierre Curie discovered that, even after uranium had decayed, the material created was still radioactive.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The material behaved somewhat similarly to barium compounds, although some properties, such as the color of the flame test and spectral lines, were much different.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] They announced the discovery of a new element on 26 December 1898 to the French Academy of Sciences.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Radium was named in 1899 from the word *radius*, meaning *ray*, as radium emitted power in the form of rays.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryllium occurs in the Earth's crust at a concentration of two to six parts per million (ppm), much of which is in soils, where it has a concentration of six ppm.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryllium is one of the rarest elements in seawater, even rarer than elements such as scandium, with a concentration of 0.2 parts per trillion.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] However, in freshwater, beryllium is somewhat more common, with a concentration of 0.1 parts per billion.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Magnesium and calcium are very common in the Earth's crust, being respectively the fifth and eighth most abundant elements.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] None of the alkaline earth metals are found in their elemental state.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Common magnesium-containing minerals are carnallite, magnesite, and dolomite.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Common calcium-containing minerals are chalk, limestone, gypsum, and anhydrite.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Strontium is the 15th most abundant element in the Earth's crust.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The principal minerals are celestite and strontianite.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Barium is slightly less common, much of it in the mineral barite.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Radium, being a decay product of uranium, is found in all uranium-bearing ores.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Due to its relatively short half-life, radium from the Earth's early history has decayed, and present-day samples have all come from the much slower decay of uranium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Production of the six alkaline earth metals can occur in many ways.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Most beryllium is extracted from beryllium hydroxide.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] One production method is sintering, done by mixing beryl, sodium fluorosilicate, and soda at high temperatures to form sodium fluoroberyllate, aluminum oxide, and silicon dioxide.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] A solution of sodium fluoroberyllate and sodium hydroxide in water is then used to form beryllium hydroxide by precipitation.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Alternatively, in the melt method, powdered beryl is heated to high temperature, cooled with water, then heated again slightly in sulfuric acid, eventually yielding beryllium hydroxide.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The beryllium hydroxide from either method then produces beryllium fluoride and beryllium chloride through a somewhat long process.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Electrolysis or heating of these compounds can then produce beryllium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] In general, strontium carbonate is extracted from the mineral celestite through two methods: by leaching the celestite with sodium carbonate, or in a more complicated way involving coal.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] To produce barium, barite (impure barium sulfate) is converted to barium sulfide by carbothermic reduction (such as with coke).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The sulfide is water-soluble and easily reacted to form pure barium sulfate, used for commercial pigments, or other compounds, such as barium nitrate.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] These in turn are calcined into barium oxide, which eventually yields pure barium after reduction with aluminum.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The most important supplier of barium is China, which produces more than 50% of world supply.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Magnesium is usually produced from magnesite ore, as well as dolomite.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] When dolomite is crushed, roasted and mixed with seawater in large tanks, magnesium hydroxide settles to the bottom.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Heating, mixing in coke, and reacting with chlorine, then produces molten magnesium chloride.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] This can be electrolyzed, releasing magnesium, which floats to the surface.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium is the fifth most abundant element in the Earth's crust, existing mostly as calcium carbonate.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Other important minerals of calcium include gypsum, anhydrite, fluorite, and apatite.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The largest producers of calcium in the world are China and Russia, where Davy's method of electrolysis is used on calcium chloride to produce the metal.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Other large producers of calcium are the U.S. and Canada, where lime is reduced with aluminium at high temperatures.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Marie Skłodowska-Curie developed the first methods of radium extraction using residues of pitchblende, following her extraction of uranium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] These residues contained mostly barium sulfate.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Curie's method was used until 1940, after which mixed bromides became more popular.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] As of 2011, radium is extracted only from spent reactor fuel as oxides.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The pure metal can be isolated by reduction with aluminium in a vacuum at 1,200 °C.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryllium is used mainly in military applications, but non-military uses exist.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] In electronics, beryllium is used as a p-type dopant in some semiconductors, and beryllium oxide is used as a high-strength electrical insulator and heat conductor.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryllium alloys are used for mechanical parts when stiffness, light weight, and dimensional stability are required over a wide temperature range.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryllium-9 is used in small-scale neutron sources that use the reaction 9Be + 4He (α) → 12C + 1n, the reaction used by James Chadwick when he discovered the neutron.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Its low atomic weight and low neutron absorption cross-section would make beryllium suitable as a neutron moderator, but its high price and the readily available alternatives such as water, heavy water and nuclear graphite have limited this to niche applications.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] In the FLiBe eutectic used in molten salt reactors, beryllium's role as a moderator is more incidental than the desired property leading to its use.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] It offers advantages over other structural materials such as aluminum, but magnesium's usage is hindered by its flammability.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Magnesium is often alloyed with aluminum, zinc and manganese to increase its strength and corrosion resistance.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Magnesium has many other industrial applications, such as its role in the production of iron and steel, and in the Kroll process for production of titanium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium is used as a reducing agent in the separation of other metals such as uranium from ore.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] It is a major component of many alloys, especially aluminum and copper alloys, and is also used to deoxidize alloys.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium has roles in the making of cheese, mortars, and cement.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Strontium and barium have fewer applications than the lighter alkaline earth metals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Strontium carbonate is used in the manufacturing of red fireworks.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Pure strontium is used in the study of neurotransmitter release in neurons.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Radioactive strontium-90 finds some use in RTGs, which utilize its decay heat.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Barium is used in vacuum tubes as a getter to remove gases.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Barium sulfate has many uses in the petroleum industry, and other industries.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Radium has many former applications based on its radioactivity, but its use is no longer common because of the adverse health effects and long half-life.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Radium was frequently used in luminous paints, although this use was stopped after it sickened workers.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The nuclear quackery that alleged health benefits of radium formerly led to its addition to drinking water, toothpaste, and many other products.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Radium is no longer used even when its radioactive properties are desired because its long half-life makes safe disposal challenging.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] For example, in brachytherapy, shorter-lived alternatives such as iridium-192 are usually used instead.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Anhydrous calcium chloride is a hygroscopic substance that is used as a desiccant.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Exposed to air, it will absorb water vapour from the air, forming a solution.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] This property is known as deliquescence.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] With carbon, they form acetylides directly.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Alkaline earth metals react with hydrogen to generate saline hydride that are unstable in water.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Ca, Sr, and Ba readily react with water to form hydroxide and hydrogen gas.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Be and Mg are passivated by an impervious layer of oxide.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] However, amalgamated magnesium will react with water vapor.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Alkaline earth metals reduce the nonmetal from its oxide.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] It dissolves in concentrated sodium hydroxide.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Magnesium reacts with alkyl halides via an insertion reaction to generate Grignard reagents.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The table below presents the colors observed when the flame of a Bunsen burner is exposed to salts of alkaline earth metals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Be and Mg do not impart colour to the flame due to their small size.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Disodium phosphate is a very selective reagent for magnesium ions and, in the presence of ammonium salts and ammonia, forms a white precipitate of ammonium magnesium phosphate.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Ca2+ forms a white precipitate with ammonium oxalate.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium oxalate is insoluble in water, but is soluble in mineral acids.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Strontium ions precipitate with soluble sulfate salts.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] All ions of alkaline earth metals form white precipitate with ammonium carbonate in the presence of ammonium chloride and ammonia.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The alkaline earth metal oxides are formed from the thermal decomposition of the corresponding carbonates.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The oxides exhibit basic character: they turn phenolphthalein red and litmus, blue.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] They react with water to form hydroxides in an exothermic reaction.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium oxide reacts with carbon to form acetylide.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] They are generated from the corresponding oxides on reaction with water.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] They exhibit basic character: they turn phenolphthalein pink and litmus, blue.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryllium hydroxide is an exception as it exhibits amphoteric character.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Ca and Mg are found in nature in many compounds such as dolomite, aragonite, magnesite (carbonate rocks).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium and magnesium ions are found in hard water.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Hard water represents a multifold issue.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] It is of great interest to remove these ions, thus softening the water.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] This procedure can be done using reagents such as calcium hydroxide, sodium carbonate or sodium phosphate.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Magnesium and calcium is essential to all known living organisms.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Magnesium is in plants, where it occurs in chlorophyll.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium ions play a large role in cell signaling, and calcium salts also take a structural role, most notably bones for vertebrates, and some shells in invertebrates.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Strontium plays an important role in marine aquatic life, especially hard corals, which use strontium to build their exoskeletons.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] In medicine, strontium compounds are employed in some toothpastes to reduce dental hypersensitivity.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] While strontium typically has a low toxicity, radioactive isotopes of strontium (like strontium-90) can be toxic.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Behaves as a "bone seeker"), it bio-accumulates with a significant biological half life, so long-term strontium-90 exposure at low concentrations can still damage the cells.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Barium has very little biological role, as soluble barium (Ba2+ ions) are toxic.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] However, in the *Loxodes* genus, an organelle known as a Müller vesicle contains barium salts, allowing the cell to orient themselves spatially using gravity.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Barium, especially its sulfate compound (BaSO4), is also used in medicine.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryllium and radium, however, are toxic.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryllium's low aqueous solubility means it is rarely available to biological systems; it has no known role in living organisms and, when encountered by them, is usually highly toxic.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Acute exposure to beryllium, typically by inhalation, causes inflammation in the airways.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Long-term exposure can cause berylliosis or Chronic beryllium disease (CBD).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Radium has a low availability and is highly radioactive, making it toxic to life.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Exposure to large amounts of radium may cause anemia, cataracts, teeth fracture and death.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Furthermore, since radium emits gamma radiation, simply being near areas with high levels of radium may be hazardous.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The next alkaline earth metal after radium is thought to be element 120, although this may not be true due to relativistic effects.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The synthesis of element 120 was first attempted in March 2007, when a team at the Flerov Laboratory of Nuclear Reactions in Dubna bombarded plutonium-244 with iron-58 ions; however, no atoms were produced, leading to a limit of 400 fb for the cross-section at the energy studied.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] In April 2007, a team at the GSI attempted to create element 120 by bombarding uranium-238 with nickel-64, although no atoms were detected, leading to a limit of 1.6 pb for the reaction.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Synthesis was again attempted at higher sensitivities, although no atoms were detected.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Other reactions have been tried, although all have been met with failure.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The chemistry of element 120 is predicted to be closer to that of calcium or strontium instead of barium or radium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] This noticeably contrasts with periodic trends, which would predict element 120 to be more reactive than barium and radium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] This lowered reactivity is due to the expected energies of element 120's valence electrons, increasing element 120's ionization energy and decreasing the metallic and ionic radii.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The next alkaline earth metal after element 120 has not been definitely predicted.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] Although a simple extrapolation using the Aufbau principle would suggest that element 170 is a congener of 120, relativistic effects may render such an extrapolation invalid.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/alkaline-earth-metal] The next element with properties similar to the alkaline earth metals has been predicted to be element 166, though due to overlapping orbitals and lower energy gap below the 9s subshell, element 166 may instead be placed in group 12, below copernicium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Chemically, aluminium is a post-transition metal in the boron group; as is common for the group, aluminium forms compounds primarily in the +3 oxidation state.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The aluminium cation Al3+ is small and highly charged; as such, it has more polarizing power, and bonds formed by aluminium have a more covalent character.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The strong affinity of aluminium for oxygen leads to the common occurrence of its oxides in nature.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is found on Earth primarily in rocks in the crust, where it is the third-most abundant element after oxygen and silicon, rather than in the mantle, and virtually never as the free metal.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] It is obtained industrially by mining bauxite, a sedimentary rock rich in aluminium minerals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The discovery of aluminium was announced in 1825 by Danish physicist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The first industrial production of aluminium was initiated by French chemist Henri Étienne Sainte-Claire Deville in 1856.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium became much more available to the public with the Hall–Héroult process developed independently by French engineer Paul Héroult and American engineer Charles Martin Hall in 1886, and the mass production of aluminium led to its extensive use in industry and everyday life.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] In 1954, aluminium became the most produced non-ferrous metal, surpassing copper.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] In the 21st century, most aluminium was consumed in transportation, engineering, construction, and packaging in the United States, Western Europe, and Japan.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The standard atomic weight of aluminium is low in comparison with many other metals, giving it the low density responsible for many of its uses.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Despite its prevalence in the environment, no living thing is known to metabolize aluminium salts, but aluminium is well tolerated by plants and animals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Because of the abundance of these salts, the potential for a biological role for them is of interest, and studies are ongoing.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium metal has an appearance ranging from silvery white to dull gray depending on its surface roughness.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium mirrors provides high reflectivity for light in the ultraviolet, visible (on par with silver), and far infrared regions.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is also good at reflecting solar radiation, although prolonged exposure to sunlight in air can deteriorate the reflectivity of the metal; this may be prevented if aluminium is anodized, which adds a protective layer of oxide on the surface.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The density of aluminium is 2.70 g/cm3, about one-third that of steel, much lower than other commonly encountered metals, making aluminium parts easily identifiable through their lightness.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium's low density compared to most other metals arises from the fact that its unit cell size is relatively large in proportion to the number of nucleons.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The only lighter metals are the metals of groups 1 and 2, which, apart from beryllium and magnesium, are too reactive for structural use (and beryllium is very toxic).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is not as strong or stiff as steel, but the low density makes up for this in the aerospace industry and for many other applications where light weight and relatively high strength are crucial.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Pure aluminium is quite soft and lacking in strength.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] In most applications, various aluminium alloys are used instead because of their higher strength and hardness.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The yield strength of pure aluminium is 7–11 MPa, while aluminium alloys have yield strengths ranging from 200 MPa to 600 MPa.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is ductile, with a percent elongation of 50–70%, and malleable allowing it to be easily drawn and extruded; it is also easily machined and cast.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is an excellent thermal and electrical conductor, and the amount of aluminium required to match the same amperage in copper weighs only half as much.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is capable of superconductivity, with a superconducting critical temperature of 1.2 kelvin and a critical magnetic field of about 100 gauss (10 milliteslas).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] It is paramagnetic and thus essentially unaffected by static magnetic fields.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] However, the high electrical conductivity means that it is strongly affected by alternating magnetic fields through the induction of eddy currents.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] An aluminium atom has 13 electrons with an electron configuration of [Ne] 3s2 3p1, with three electrons beyond a stable noble gas configuration.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Accordingly, the combined first three ionization energies of aluminium are far lower than the fourth ionization energy alone.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Such an electron configuration is shared with the other well-characterized members of its group, boron, gallium, indium, and thallium; it is also expected for nihonium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium can surrender its three outermost electrons in many chemical reactions (see below).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The electronegativity of aluminium is 1.61 on the Pauling scale.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] A free aluminium atom has an atomic radius of 143 pm.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] With the three outermost electrons removed, the radius shrinks to 39 pm for a 4-coordinated atom or 53.5 pm for a 6-coordinated atom.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] At standard temperature and pressure, aluminium atoms (when not affected by atoms of other elements) form a face-centered cubic crystal system bound by metallic bonding provided by atoms' outermost electrons; hence, aluminium (at these conditions) is a metal.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] This crystal system is shared by many other metals, such as lead and copper; the size of a unit cell of aluminium is comparable to that of those other metals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] This system, however, is not shared by the other members of its group: boron has ionization energies too high to allow metallization, thallium has a hexagonal close-packed structure, and gallium and indium have unusual structures that are not close-packed like those of aluminium and thallium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The few electrons that are available for metallic bonding in aluminium are a probable cause for it being soft with a low melting point and low electrical resistivity.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium has one stable isotope, 27Al, which comprises virtually all of the naturally-occurring element.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] This is common for elements with an odd atomic number.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] It is therefore a mononuclidic element for standard atomic weight, which is determined completely by that isotope.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is useful in nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR), as its single stable isotope (though quadrupolar) has a high NMR sensitivity.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] All other isotopes of aluminium are radioactive.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The most stable of these is 26Al, with a half-life of 717,000 years.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] While it was present along with stable 27Al in the interstellar medium from which the Solar System formed (believed to have been produced by stellar nucleosynthesis also), no detectable amount could have survived the time since the formation of the planet.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] However, minute traces of 26Al are still produced from decay of argon in the atmosphere induced by ionizing radiation of cosmic rays.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The ratio of 26Al to 10Be has been used for the radiodating of geological processes over 105 to 106 year time scales, in particular transport, deposition, sediment storage, burial times, and erosion.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Most meteorite scientists believe that the energy released by the decay of 26Al was responsible for the melting and differentiation of some asteroids after their formation 4.55 billion years ago.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The other known isotopes of aluminium, with mass numbers ranging from 20 to 43, all have half-lives less than 7 minutes, as do the four detected metastable states.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium combines characteristics of pre- and post-transition metals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Since it has few available electrons for metallic bonding, like the heavier group 13 elements, it has the characteristic physical properties of a post-transition metal, with longer-than-expected interatomic distances.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Furthermore, as Al3+ is a small and highly charged cation, it is strongly polarizing, and bonding in aluminium compounds tends towards covalency; this behavior is similar to that of beryllium (Be2+), displaying an example of a diagonal relationship.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The underlying core of electrons under aluminium's valence shell is that of the preceding noble gas, whereas those of the heavier group 13 elements gallium, indium, thallium, and nihonium also include a filled d-subshell and in some cases a filled f-subshell.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Hence, the inner electrons of aluminium shield the valence electrons almost completely, unlike those of the heavier group 13 elements.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] As such, aluminium is the most electropositive metal in its group, and its hydroxide is in fact more basic than that of gallium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium also bears minor similarities to boron (a metalloid), which is in the same group: AlX3 compounds are valence isoelectronic to BX3 compounds (they have the same valence electronic structure), and both behave as Lewis acids and readily form adducts.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Additionally, one of the main motifs of boron chemistry is regular icosahedral structures, and aluminium forms an important part of many icosahedral quasicrystal alloys, including the Al–Zn–Mg class.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium has a high chemical affinity to oxygen, which renders it suitable for use as a reducing agent in the thermite reaction.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] A fine powder of aluminium reacts explosively on contact with liquid oxygen; under normal conditions, however, aluminium forms a thin oxide layer (~5 nm at room temperature) that protects the metal from further corrosion by oxygen, water, or dilute acid, a process termed passivation.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is not attacked by oxidizing acids because of its passivation.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] This allows aluminium to be used to store reagents such as nitric acid, concentrated sulfuric acid, and some organic acids.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] In hot, concentrated hydrochloric acid, aluminium reacts with water through evolution of hydrogen, and it reacts in aqueous sodium or potassium hydroxide at room temperature to form aluminates; protective passivation under these conditions is negligible.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is also corroded by dissolved chlorides, such as common sodium chloride.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The oxide layer on aluminium is also destroyed by contact with mercury due to amalgamation or by contact with salts of some electropositive metals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] As such, the strongest aluminium alloys are less corrosion-resistant due to galvanic reactions with alloyed copper, and aluminium's corrosion resistance is greatly reduced by aqueous salts, particularly in the presence of dissimilar metals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium reacts with most nonmetals upon heating, forming compounds such as aluminium nitride (AlN), aluminium sulfide (Al2S3), and the aluminium halides (AlX3).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] It also forms a wide range of intermetallic compounds involving metals from every group on the periodic table.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The vast majority of aluminium compounds, including all aluminium-containing minerals and all commercially significant aluminium compounds, feature aluminium in the oxidation state 3+.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The coordination number of such compounds varies, but generally Al3+ is either six- or four-coordinate.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Almost all compounds of aluminium(III) are colorless.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] In aqueous solution, Al3+ exists as the hexa-aqua cation [Al(H2O)6]3+, which has an approximate Ka of 10−5.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Such solutions are acidic because this cation can act as a proton donor and progressively hydrolyze until a precipitate of aluminium hydroxide, Al(OH)3, forms.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] This is useful for clarification of water, since the precipitate nucleates on suspended particles in the water, hence removing them.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Increasing the pH even further leads to the hydroxide dissolving again as aluminate, [Al(H2O)2(OH)4]−, is formed.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium hydroxide forms both salts and aluminates and dissolves in acid and alkali, as well as on fusion with acidic and basic oxides.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] This behavior of Al(OH)3 is termed amphoterism and is characteristic of weakly basic cations that form insoluble hydroxides and whose hydrated species can also donate their protons.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] One effect of this is that aluminium salts with weak acids are hydrolyzed in water to the aquated hydroxide and the corresponding nonmetal hydride: for example, aluminium sulfide yields hydrogen sulfide.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] However, some salts like aluminium carbonate exist in aqueous solution but are unstable as such.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Only incomplete hydrolysis takes place for salts with strong acids, such as the halides, nitrate, and sulfate.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] For similar reasons, anhydrous aluminium salts cannot be made by heating their "hydrates": hydrated aluminium chloride is in fact not AlCl3·6H2O but [Al(H2O)6]Cl3, and the Al–O bonds are so strong that heating is not sufficient to break them and form Al–Cl bonds.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Unlike the structures of the three heavier trihalides, aluminium fluoride (AlF3) features six-coordinate aluminium, which explains its involatility and insolubility as well as high heat of formation.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Each aluminium atom is surrounded by six fluorine atoms in a distorted octahedral arrangement, with each fluorine atom being shared between the corners of two octahedra.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Such {AlF6} units also exist in complex fluorides such as cryolite, Na3AlF6.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] AlF3 melts at 1,290 °C (2,354 °F) and is made by reaction of aluminium oxide with hydrogen fluoride gas at 700 °C (1,300 °F).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] With heavier halides, the coordination numbers are lower.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The other trihalides are dimeric or polymeric with tetrahedral four-coordinate aluminium centers.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium trichloride (AlCl3) has a layered polymeric structure below its melting point of 192.4 °C (378 °F) but transforms on melting to Al2Cl6 dimers.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] At higher temperatures those increasingly dissociate into trigonal planar AlCl3 monomers similar to the structure of BCl3.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium tribromide and aluminium triiodide form Al2X6 dimers in all three phases and hence do not show such significant changes of properties upon phase change.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] These materials are prepared by treating aluminium with the halogen.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The aluminium trihalides form many addition compounds or complexes.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Their Lewis acidic nature makes them useful as catalysts for the Friedel–Crafts reactions.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium trichloride has major industrial uses involving this reaction, such as in the manufacture of anthraquinones and styrene.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium trichloride is also often used as the precursor for many other aluminium compounds and as a reagent for converting nonmetal fluorides into the corresponding chlorides (a transhalogenation reaction).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium forms one stable oxide with the chemical formula Al2O3, commonly called alumina.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] It can be found in nature in the mineral corundum, the α-alumina phase.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Its crystalline form, corundum, is very hard (Mohs hardness 9), has a high melting point of 2,045 °C (3,713 °F), has very low volatility, is chemically inert, and is a good electrical insulator.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] It is often used in abrasives (such as sandpaper) as a refractory material and in ceramics.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] It is also the starting material for the electrolytic production of aluminium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Sapphire and ruby are impure corundum contaminated with trace amounts of other metals.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The two main oxide-hydroxides, AlO(OH), are boehmite and diaspore.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] There are three main trihydroxides: bayerite, gibbsite, and nordstrandite, which differ in their crystalline structure (polymorphs).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Many other intermediate and related structures are also known.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Most of these Al-O-OH systems are produced from ores by a variety of wet processes using acid and bases.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Heating the hydroxides leads to the formation of corundum.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] These materials are of central importance to the production of aluminium and are themselves extremely useful.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Some mixed oxide phases are also very useful, such as spinel (MgAl2O4), Na-β-alumina (NaAl11O17), and tricalcium aluminate (Ca3Al2O6), an important mineral phase in Portland cement.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The only stable chalcogenides under normal conditions are aluminium sulfide (Al2S3), selenide (Al2Se3), and telluride (Al2Te3).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] All three are prepared by direct reaction of their elements at about 1,000 °C (1,800 °F) and quickly hydrolyze completely in water to yield aluminium hydroxide and the respective hydrogen chalcogenide.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] As aluminium is a small atom relative to these chalcogens, these have four-coordinate tetrahedral aluminium with various polymorphs having structures related to wurtzite, with two-thirds of the possible metal sites occupied either in an orderly (α) or random (β) fashion.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The sulfide also has a γ form related to γ-alumina and an unusual high-temperature hexagonal form where half the aluminium atoms have tetrahedral four-coordination and the other half have trigonal bipyramidal five-coordination.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Four pnictides – aluminium nitride (AlN), aluminium phosphide (AlP), aluminium arsenide (AlAs), and aluminium antimonide (AlSb) – are known.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] They are all III-V semiconductors isoelectronic to silicon and germanium, all of which but AlN have the zinc blende structure.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] All four can be made by high-temperature (and possibly high-pressure) direct reaction of their component elements.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium alloys well with most other metals (with the exception of most alkali metals and group 13 metals) and over 150 intermetallics with other metals are known.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Preparation involves heating fixed metals together in certain proportions, followed by gradual cooling and annealing.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Bonding in them is predominantly metallic and the crystal structure primarily depends on efficiency of packing.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] There are few compounds with lower oxidation states.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Some are aluminium(I) compounds: AlF, AlCl, AlBr, and AlI all exist in the gaseous phase when the respective trihalide is heated with aluminium, and at cryogenic temperatures.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] A stable derivative of aluminium monoiodide is the cyclic adduct formed with triethylamine, Al4I4(NEt3)4.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Al2O and Al2S also exist but are very unstable.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Very simple aluminium(II) compounds are invoked or observed in the reactions of Al metal with oxidants.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] For example, aluminium monoxide, AlO, has been detected in the gas phase after explosion and in stellar absorption spectra.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] More thoroughly investigated are compounds of the formula R4Al2 which contain an Al–Al bond and where R is a large organic ligand.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] A variety of compounds of empirical formula AlR3 and AlR1.5Cl1.5 exist.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The aluminium trialkyls and triaryls are either reactive, volatile, and colorless liquids or low-melting solids.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] They catch fire spontaneously in air and react with water, thus necessitating precautions when handling them.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] They often form dimers, unlike their boron analogues, but this tendency diminishes for branched-chain alkyls (e.g.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] For example, triisobutylaluminium exists as an equilibrium mixture of the monomer and dimer.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] These dimers, such as trimethylaluminium (Al2Me6), usually feature tetrahedral Al centers formed by dimerization with some alkyl group bridging between both aluminium atoms.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] They are hard acids and react readily with ligands, forming adducts.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] In industry, they are mostly used in alkene insertion reactions, as discovered by Karl Ziegler, most importantly in "growth reactions" that form long-chain unbranched primary alkenes and alcohols, and in the low-pressure polymerization of ethene and propene.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] There are also some heterocyclic and cluster organoaluminium compounds involving Al–N bonds.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The industrially most important aluminium hydride is lithium aluminium hydride (LiAlH4), which is used as a reducing agent in organic chemistry.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] It can be produced from lithium hydride and aluminium trichloride.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The simplest hydride, aluminium hydride or alane, is not as important.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] It is a polymer with the formula (AlH3)*n*, which is in contrast to the corresponding boron hydride that is a dimer with the formula (BH3)2.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium's per-particle abundance in the Solar System is 3.15 ppm (parts per million).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] It is the twelfth most abundant of all elements and third most abundant among the elements that have odd atomic numbers, after hydrogen and nitrogen.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The only stable isotope of aluminium, 27Al, is the eighteenth most abundant nucleus in the universe.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] It is created almost entirely after fusion of carbon in massive stars that will later become Type II supernovas: this fusion creates 26Mg, which upon capturing free protons and neutrons, becomes aluminium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Some smaller quantities of 27Al are created in hydrogen burning shells of evolved stars, where 26Mg can capture free protons.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Essentially all aluminium now in existence is 27Al.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] 26Al was present in the early Solar System with abundance of 0.005% relative to 27Al but its half-life of 728,000 years is too short for any original nuclei to survive; 26Al is therefore extinct.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Unlike for 27Al, hydrogen burning is the primary source of 26Al, with the nuclide emerging after a nucleus of 25Mg catches a free proton.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] However, the trace quantities of 26Al that do exist are the most common gamma ray emitter in the interstellar gas; if the original 26Al were still present, gamma ray maps of the Milky Way would be brighter.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Overall, the Earth is about 1.59% aluminium by mass (seventh in abundance by mass).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium occurs in greater proportion in the Earth's crust than in the universe at large.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] This is because aluminium easily forms the oxide and becomes bound into rocks and stays in the Earth's crust, while less reactive metals sink to the core.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] In the Earth's crust, aluminium is the most abundant metallic element (8.23% by mass) and the third most abundant of all elements (after oxygen and silicon).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] A large number of silicates in the Earth's crust contain aluminium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] In contrast, the Earth's mantle is only 2.38% aluminium by mass.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium also occurs in seawater at a concentration of 0.41 μg/kg.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Because of its strong affinity for oxygen, aluminium is almost never found in the elemental state; instead it is found in oxides or silicates.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Feldspars, the most common group of minerals in the Earth's crust, are aluminosilicates.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium also occurs in the minerals beryl, cryolite, garnet, spinel, and turquoise.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Impurities in alumina yield gemstones: for example, chromium yields ruby and iron yields sapphire.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Native aluminium metal is extremely rare and can only be found as a minor phase in low oxygen fugacity environments, such as the interiors of certain volcanoes.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Native aluminium has been reported in cold seeps in the northeastern continental slope of the South China Sea.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] It is possible that these deposits resulted from bacterial reduction of tetrahydroxoaluminate Al(OH)4−.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Although aluminium is a common and widespread element, not all aluminium minerals are economically viable sources of the metal.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Almost all metallic aluminium is produced from the ore bauxite (AlO*x*(OH)3–2*x*).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Bauxite occurs as a weathering product of low iron and silica bedrock in tropical climatic conditions.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] In 2017, most bauxite was mined in Australia, China, Guinea, and India.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The history of aluminium has been shaped by usage of alum.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The first written record of alum, made by Greek historian Herodotus, dates back to the 5th century BCE.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The ancients are known to have used alum as a dyeing mordant and for city defense as a fire-resistant coating for wood.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] After the Crusades, alum, an indispensable good in the European fabric industry, was a subject of international commerce; it was imported to Europe from the eastern Mediterranean until the mid-15th century.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The nature of alum remained unknown until Swiss physician Paracelsus suggested alum was a salt of an earth of alum around 1530.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] German doctor and chemist Andreas Libavius experimentally confirmed this in 1595.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] German chemist Friedrich Hoffmann announced his belief that the base of alum was a distinct earth in 1722.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] German chemist Andreas Sigismund Marggraf synthesized alumina in 1754 by boiling clay in sulfuric acid and subsequently adding potash.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Attempts to produce aluminium date back to 1760.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The first successful attempt, however, was completed in 1824 by Danish physicist and chemist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] He reacted anhydrous aluminium chloride with potassium amalgam, yielding a lump of metal looking similar to tin.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] He presented his results and demonstrated a sample of the new metal in 1825.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] In 1827, German chemist Friedrich Wöhler repeated Ørsted's experiments but did not identify any aluminium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] (The reason for this inconsistency was only discovered in 1921.) He conducted a similar experiment in the same year by mixing anhydrous aluminium chloride with potassium (the Wöhler process) and produced a powder of aluminium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] In 1845, he was able to produce small pieces of the metal and described some physical properties of this metal.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] For many years thereafter, Wöhler was credited as the discoverer of aluminium.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] As Wöhler's method could not yield great quantities of aluminium, the metal remained rare; its cost exceeded that of gold.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The first industrial production of aluminium was established in 1856 by French chemist Henri Étienne Sainte-Claire Deville and companions.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Sainte-Claire Deville had discovered that aluminium trichloride could be reduced by sodium, which was more convenient and less expensive than potassium, which Wöhler had used.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Even then, aluminium was still not of great purity and produced aluminium differed in properties by sample.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Because of its electricity-conducting capacity, aluminium was used as the cap of the Washington Monument, completed in 1885, the tallest building in the world at the time.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The non-corroding metal cap was intended to serve as a lightning rod peak.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The first industrial large-scale production method was independently developed in 1886 by French engineer Paul Héroult and American engineer Charles Martin Hall; it is now known as the Hall–Héroult process.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The Hall–Héroult process converts alumina into metal.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Austrian chemist Carl Joseph Bayer discovered a way of purifying bauxite to yield alumina, now known as the Bayer process, in 1889.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Modern production of aluminium is based on the Bayer and Hall–Héroult processes.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] As large-scale production caused aluminium prices to drop, the metal became widely used in jewelry, eyeglass frames, optical instruments, tableware, and foil, and other everyday items in the 1890s and early 20th century.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Aluminium's ability to form hard yet light alloys with other metals provided the metal with many uses at the time.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] During World War I, major governments demanded large shipments of aluminium for light strong airframes; during World War II, demand by major governments for aviation was even higher.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] From the early 20th century to 1980, the aluminium industry was characterized by cartelization, as aluminium firms colluded to keep prices high and stable.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The first aluminium cartel, the Aluminium Association, was founded in 1901 by the Pittsburgh Reduction Company (renamed Alcoa in 1907) and Aluminium Industrie AG.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The British Aluminium Company, Produits Chimiques d'Alais et de la Camargue, and Société Électro-Métallurgique de Froges also joined the cartel.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] By the mid-20th century, aluminium had become a part of everyday life and an essential component of housewares.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] In 1954, production of aluminium surpassed that of copper, historically second in production only to iron, making it the most produced non-ferrous metal.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] During the mid-20th century, aluminium emerged as a civil engineering material, with building applications in both basic construction and interior finish work, and increasingly being used in military engineering, for both airplanes and armored vehicle engines.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Earth's first artificial satellite, launched in 1957, consisted of two separate aluminium semi-spheres joined and all subsequent space vehicles have used aluminium to some extent.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The aluminium can was invented in 1956 and employed as a storage for drinks in 1958.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Throughout the 20th century, the production of aluminium rose rapidly: while the world production of aluminium in 1900 was 6,800 metric tons, the annual production first exceeded 100,000 metric tons in 1916; 1,000,000 tons in 1941; 10,000,000 tons in 1971.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] In the 1970s, the increased demand for aluminium made it an exchange commodity; it entered the London Metal Exchange, the oldest industrial metal exchange in the world, in 1978.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The output continued to grow: the annual production of aluminium exceeded 50,000,000 metric tons in 2013.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The real price for aluminium declined from $14,000 per metric ton in 1900 to $2,340 in 1948 (in 1998 United States dollars).
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Extraction and processing costs were lowered over technological progress and the scale of the economies.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] However, the need to exploit lower-grade poorer quality deposits and the use of fast increasing input costs (above all, energy) increased the net cost of aluminium; the real price began to grow in the 1970s with the rise of energy cost.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Production moved from the industrialized countries to countries where production was cheaper.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] Production costs in the late 20th century changed because of advances in technology, lower energy prices, exchange rates of the United States dollar, and alumina prices.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] The BRIC countries' combined share in primary production and primary consumption grew substantially in the first decade of the 21st century.
[src:enthalpy-of-vaporization/aluminium-p01] China is accumulating an especially large share of the world's production thanks to an abundance of resources, cheap energy, and governmental stimuli; it also increased its consumption share from 2% in 1972 to 40% in 2010.
